Name: Dicyclopentadiene
Rationale for classification: Classification not possible due to lack of data

Name: Coal tar naphtha
Rationale for classification: Category 5 because of SPECIES: Rat; ENDPOINT: LC50 (4-8h) VALUE: 5.3mg/L (EHC20, 1982)

Name: p-Dichlorobenzene
Rationale for classification: Because the rat LC50 (4-hour inhalation) value of 5.07mg/L (equivalent to 845ppm) (CERI-NITE Hazard Assessment No.76 (2005)) was higher than 110% of the saturated vapour concentration (790ppm, 20degC), the substance was considered as "dust exposure containing vapour" and was classified based on the dust classification.

Name: Complex compounds of manganese N,N'-ethylenebis(dithiocarbamate) and zinc N,N'-ethylenebis(dithiocarbamate)
Rationale for classification: Based on the absence of mortality at the highest dose of 5.08mg/L in rat inhalation studies (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1993)).

Name: Methyl 3-chloro-5-(4,6-dimethoxy-2-pyrimidinylcarbamoylsulfamoyl)-1-methylpyrazole-4-carboxylate
Rationale for classification: Based on the rat LC50 (inhalation route) value of >6.0mg/L (4 hours), together with the absence of mortality (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1990)).

Name: propaphos
Rationale for classification: It was set as Category 1 based on LC50 = 0.039mg/L on the both sex rat (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data).

Name: Methacrylic acid
Rationale for classification: Because the rat LC50 (4-hour inhalation exposure) value of 7.1mg/L (equivalent to 2,000ppm) (EU-RAR No.25 (2002)) exceeded the saturated vapour concentration (900ppm) under a saturated vapour pressure of 0.09kPa (20degC), the substance was considered as "mist exposure."

Name: Bromine
Rationale for classification: Classification not possible due to lack of data

Name: Adiponitrile
Rationale for classification: Based on the testing data of rat LC50 (inhalation of dust/mist) of 1.71mg/L (SIDS, 1998).

Name: S-1-methyl-1-phenylethyl 1-piperidinecarbothioate
Rationale for classification: Classification not possible due to the insufficiency of data.

Name: caesium hydroxide
Rationale for classification: The value of 0.02mg/L was found in the inhalation LC50 data in which the animal and time of exposure was unknown (RTECS (2004)), it was considered as dust inhalation "category 1". Data that human LC50 (?): 0.005mg/L was also in the same former literature.

Name: Lead, tetraethyl-
Rationale for classification: Classification not possible due to lack of data

Name: Chlorotrifluoromethane; CFC-13
Rationale for classification: Due to the fact that the substance is "gas" according to the GHS definition and inhalation of its dust/mist is not expected.

Name: m-Chloroaniline
Rationale for classification: Based on the rat LD50 (4 hour inhalation exposure) value of 0.783mg/L (equivalent to 150ppm) (MOE Risk Assessment vol.2 (2003)) was higher than the saturated vapour concentration of 90 ppm under a saturated vapour pressure of 9Pa (20degC), the substance was considered as "mist exposure."

Name: Sodium bromate
Rationale for classification: Classification not possible due to lack of data

Name: O-4-bromo-2-chlorophenyl O-ethyl S-propyl phosphorothioate
Rationale for classification: Based on the rat LC50 (inhalation route) value of 4.45mg/kg (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1984)).

Name: Dimethyl 2,2,2-trichloro-1-hydroxyethylphosphonate; Trichlorfon; DEP
Rationale for classification: Classification not possible because there is no evidence of death at the highest dose of 2.3mg/kg in rat inhalation exposure studies, and the acute toxicity value cannot be determined (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1997)).

Name: Diiron trioxide
Rationale for classification: Since this product is solid form and most vapor pressures can be disregarded, it is thought that the inhalation study was done with the dust. Since there was no study in which LC50 value was acquired, data is insufficient and it cannot be classified.

Name: ammonium pentadecafluorooctanoate
Rationale for classification: There was description that the fatal doses by rat 4-hour inhalation exposure was 0.8mg/L or more (ACGIH (7th, 2001)). But there is no other data. Therefore, it cannot be classified since data is insufficient.

Name: Aniline
Rationale for classification: Based on the LC50 value (4 hours) of 2.3mg/L, calculated from the testing data of rat LC50 (inhalation of vapor) of 5.1mg/L (4 hours) (CaPSAR (1994)), 3.3mg/L (4 hours) (EU-RAR No.50 (2004)), 3.19mg/L(4 hours) (EU-RAR No.50 (2004)), 1.82mg/L (4 hours) (EU-RAR No.50 (2004)) was higher than of the saturated vapor concentration (400ppm) under a saturated vapour pressure of 0.04kPa (25degC) (ICSC (2004)), the substance was considered as "mist".

Name: Poly(oxyethylene) alkyl ether (alkyl C=12-15)
Rationale for classification: Based on the rat LC50 (inhalation route) value of 1.5mg/L (alkyl C12-13, EO6) (4 hours).

Name: S,S,S-tributylphosphorotrithioate
Rationale for classification: It was set as Category 3 based on mouse inhalation LC50 (1hr) = 3804mg/m3 (RTECS (2004)) (4-hour equivalent 0.951mg/L). The saturated concentration of this product is 0.0168ppm (equivalent 0.22mg/m3), and it is presumed that the experiment was conducted in mist conditions.

Name: Phosphorus pentachloride
Rationale for classification:
There was a statement of rat LC50: 0.205mg/L (RTECS (2004)). But it was presupposed that test time is unstated. Therefore, it cannot be classified since data is insufficient.
However, when there are necessities, such as a display, handling similar to category 2 is recommended from a viewpoint of safety.

Name: Sodium azide  (Na(N3))
Rationale for classification: It cannot taxonomic according to lack of information. The information on RTECS (2004) is not clear in a chemical exposure forms. (a dust, cracked gas)

Name: 2-(1,3-Thiazol-4-yl)-1H-benzoimidazole
Rationale for classification: Saturated vapor pressure level at 25degCis 8.23*10^-5 mg/m3. Since LC50 value with >0.4 mg/L of the 4-hour inhalation exposure test employing rats (JECFA (2001)) is larger than saturated vapor pressure level, classification cannot be specified when applying the dust and mist standard, and classification is not possible.

Name: Distillates (petroleum), straight-run middle
Rationale for classification: Inhalation study of gasoline was done that aerosol is mixed with steam, it was thought that aerosol is main. And It was set as Category 4 based on value 4.6mg/L (IUCLID (2000)) that is lower value of rat inhalation LC50.

Name: Methamidophos
Rationale for classification: Based on the rat LC50 (4 hour inhalation of dust) value of 0.162mg/L (RTECS (2006)).

Name: Morpholine, 4-ethyl-
Rationale for classification: Classification not possible due to lack of data

Name: O,O-Dimethyl S-(N-methylcarbamoyl)methyl phosphorodithioate; Dimethoate
Rationale for classification: The available rat inhalation studies yielded the LC50 (4 hour) value of >0.900mg/L (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1986)). However, classification is not possible because there is no evidence of death at the highest dose of 0.900mg/L, and the acute toxicity value cannot be determined.

Name: O,O-Dimethyl S-2-[1-(N-methylcarbamoyl)ethylthio]ethyl phosphorothioate; Vamidothion
Rationale for classification: Based on the rat LC50 (inhalation of dust/mist) value of 1.730mg/L (4 hours) (RTECS (2006)).

Name: 2-chloro-4,6-bis(ethylamino)-1,3,5-triazine
Rationale for classification: Based on the rat LC50 (inhalation route) value of >5.6mg/L, together with the absence of mortality (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (2005)).

Name: potassium nitrite
Rationale for classification: It was set as Category 5 based on mouse LC50 value 42mg/L/4H (85g/m3/2H) (RTECS, 1997).

Name: 1,2-dimethoxyethane
Rationale for classification: Classification not possible due to lack of data

Name: Ethanaminium, 2-chloro-N,N,N-trimethyl-
Rationale for classification: It was set as Category 5 based on rat LC0 = 3.05mg/L and LC10-20 = 5.2mg/L (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data).

Name: 2-Butenal
Rationale for classification: Classification not possible due to lack of data

Name: beryllium
Rationale for classification: Since data is insufficient, it cannot classify. There is only a description in ATSDR (2002) that 20 out of 74 rats died on 12 - 15 days after from 50-minute inhalation exposure of 0.8 mg/L..

Name: dinoseb acetate
Rationale for classification: Since rat inhalation LC50 (4h) = 1.3mg/L (RTECS (1997)), it was set as category 4. In addition, the saturated concentration of this product is about 0.01mg/L, and it is presumed that the inhalation study is done in dust and mists conditions.

Name: dioxacarb
Rationale for classification: There is the knowledge that rat LC50 = 160mg/m3 (RTECS (2003)). But exposure time is unknown and it cannot taxonomic according to insufficient data.

Name: Distillates (petroleum), solvent-refined heavy paraffinic; Distillates (petroleum), solvent-refined light naphthenic; Lubricating oils (petroleum), C15-30, hydrotreated neutral oil-based; Lubricating oils (petroleum), C20-50, hydrotreated neutral oil-based; Petroleum; Paraffin oils
Rationale for classification: Category 4 because of "SPECIES: Rat;  ENDPOINT: LC50 = 2.18 mg/L." (IUCLID, 2000)

Name: Acrylic acid
Rationale for classification: Based on the LC50 value (4 hours) calculated from the testing data of rat LC50 (inhalation of mist) of 11.1 mg/L (1 hour) and 7.5 mg/L (2 hours) (EHC 191 (1997)). Of LC50 values of 2.8 and 3.8 mg/L (4 hours) calculated, the lower value was adopted for classification purposes.

Name: Fenamiphos
Rationale for classification: Category 2 because of "SPECIES: Rat;  ENDPOINT: LC50 ; VALUE: 0.091-0.10 mg/L (4 h)" (JMPR 929, 1997)

Name: 3,5-Dimethylphenyl N-methylcarbamate; XMC
Rationale for classification: Classification not possible since the acute toxicity value cannot be determined, though the available rat inhalation studies yielded the LC50 value of >=1.02mg/L (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (2004)).

Name: pyrogallol
Rationale for classification: Classification is not possible because there is no data. In addition, EU Annex I is Xn; R20/21/22, and is equivalent to the GHS Category 3-4.

Name: Phosgene
Rationale for classification: Due to the fact that the substance is "gas" according to the GHS definition and inhalation of its dust/mist is not expected.

Name: Hexadecan-1-yl(trimethyl)ammonium chloride
Rationale for classification: Classification not possible due to lack of data

Name: Polymer of N,N'-propylenebis(dithiocarbamic acid) and zinc
Rationale for classification: Classification cannot be determined, though the available rat inhalation study reported the LC50 value of >0.557mg/L (4 hours) (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1968)).

Name: O,O-Diethyl O-5-phenyl-3-isoxazolyl phosphorothioate; Isoxathion Â
Rationale for classification: Based on the rat LC50 (inhalation route) value of 2.0mg/L (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1985)).

Name: Benzophenone
Rationale for classification: Classification not possible due to lack of data

Name: 2-[(Tolyloxy)methyl]oxirane
Rationale for classification: Since it is written that LC50 value of the 4-hour inhalation exposure test employing rats is 1,220 ppm (equivalent: 8.19 mg/L) (Patty (5th, 2001), it was classified into "Not classified" by applying the mist standard from saturated vapor pressure level of this substance (25degC)with 0.38 mg/L . In addition, it is written in the information source of List2 that LC50 value of aerosol inhalation exposure test employing rats is 4.8-8.5 mg/L (IUCLID (2000)).

Name: Acetophenone
Rationale for classification: The saturated vapor pressures concentrations pressure of acetophenones is 523.7ppm (25degC), it is presumed that the inhalation study was done in the state of steam. There is no data about mists.

Name: Oleum
Rationale for classification: It was set as Category 3 based on rat inhalation LC50 = 347ppm/1H (= 86.7ppm/4H = 0.63mg/L/4H, molecular weights are set to 178.14, and it is guessed as mist) (RTECS (1995)).

Name: 3,6-Bis(2-chlorophenyl)-1,2,4,5-tetrazine; Clofentezine
Rationale for classification: Classification not possible due to the insufficiency of data.

Name: Diisopropyl 1,3-dithiolan-2-ylidenemalonate; isoprothiolane
Rationale for classification: It was set as category 4 based on rat inhalation (particulate and mist) LC50 value ( >2.77mg/L: Agricultural Chemical Registration Data, 2001). In addition, although LC50 value was not specified, 4 is in the range of 1.0 <Category 4 = <5.0mg/L.

Name: 2-(4-Bromodifluoromethoxyphenyl)-2-methylpropyl 3-phenoxybenzyl ether; Hhalfenprox
Rationale for classification: Based on the rat LC50 (inhalation route) value of 0.36mg/L (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1993)).

Name: N-Phenylmaleimide
Rationale for classification: Classification not possible due to lack of data

Name: tricarbonyl(eta-cyclopentadienyl)manganese
Rationale for classification: There was information (ACGIH (2001)) that 80% died from 4-hour exchange 0.06mg/L, and that LC50 was near 0.05 mg/L. So it was set as Category 1.

Name: Atrazine
Rationale for classification: In both LC50 >5.82mg/L (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data, 2002) and >5.148mg/L (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data, 1991) of an inhalation exposure test using rats, no death cases were repoted.  But the oral acute toxicities of category 4 were indicated, it was set as Category 5. In addition, the saturated concentration of this product is 3.81*10^(-4)ppm (equivalent 3.36*10^(-6)mg/L), and it is presumed that all inhalation tests are done in dust mists conditions.

Name: BHC or HCH
Rationale for classification: It was set as category 3 base on rat inhalation LC50 (4hr) = 0.69mg/L (RTECS (2004)). In addition, considering the saturated concentration (about 0.01mg/L) computed from this substance's steam pressure (0.1Pa at 25degC), it was presumed that the experiment was conducted in dust and mists conditions.

Name: Emamectin benzoate
Rationale for classification: It was set as category 4 based on rat LC50 = 1.93mg/L (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data) of an inhalation exposure test.

Name: fonofos
Rationale for classification: Since the saturated vapor pressures concentrations pressure of this product is 0.49ppm, it is thought that the inhalation study was done in mist. Based on LC50 = 0.225mg/L (4-hour equivalent) which is the lower one among the rat inhalation 2 data (ACGIH (2001)), it was set as Category 2.

Name: 2,2-Dichloropropionic acid
Rationale for classification: Since rat LC50 value of the inhalation exposure test (dust mists) is indicated male and females: >4.15mg/L/4H (100% purity equivalent: >1.25mg/L/4H))(Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1999)), it was set as Category 4.

Name: 1-({2-[2-chloro-4-(4-chlorophenoxy)phenyl]-4-methyl-1,3-dioxolan-2-yl}methyl)-1H-1,2,4-triazole
Rationale for classification: Based on the rat LC50 (inhalation route) value of 3.29mg/L (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1992)).

Name: 2-Amino-4-[hydroxy(methyl)phosphinoyl]butyric acid; Glufosinate
Rationale for classification: Based on the rat LC50 (inhalation route) value of 1.26mg/L (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1986)).

Name: N-(1-Ethylpropyl)-2,6-dinitro-3,4-xylidine; Pendimethalin
Rationale for classification: Based on the rat LC50 (inhalation route) value of >320mg/L (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1993)).

Name: tert-Dodecanethiol
Rationale for classification: Since it is written that there was no mortality with 2.1 mg/L in 4-hour inhalation exposure test employing rats (Patty (5th, 2001)), LC50 value is considered to be >2.1 mg/L. When applying the dust standard from saturated vapor pressure level of this substance (20degC)with 0.27 mg/L, classification cannot be specified, classification is not possible.

Name: methyl 2-[[[[(4,6-dimethyl-2-pyrimidinyl)amino]carbonyl]amino]sulphonyl]benzoate
Rationale for classification: Based on description that "there is no death in male and female rats after 4-hour inhalation exposure of 11000mg/m3" (ACGIH (2001)), it was set as the outside of Category. (11000mg/m3 = 11mg/L)

Name: Distillates (petroleum), solvent-refined heavy paraffinic; Distillates (petroleum), solvent-refined light naphthenic; Lubricating oils (petroleum), C15-30, hydrotreated neutral oil-based; Lubricating oils (petroleum), C20-50, hydrotreated neutral oil-based; Petroleum; Paraffin oils
Rationale for classification: Category 4 because of "SPECIES: Rat;  ENDPOINT: LC50 = 2.18 mg/L." (IUCLID, 2000)

Name: (1'S,6'R)-7-Chloro-2',4,6-trimethoxy-6'-methyl-3H-spiro[benzofuran-2,1'-cyclohex[2]ene]-3,4'-dione
Rationale for classification: Classification not possible due to lack of data

Name: sodium 4,6-dinitro-o-cresolate
Rationale for classification:
Data without.
(In the risk phrases of EU-Annex I (Access on Aug.2005), it is supposed  that inhalation toxicity is high.)

Name: Disodium chromate decahydrate
Rationale for classification: Rat LC50 = 0.104mg/L/4h to the sodium chromate anhydrides (CAS:7775-11-3) carried out in the state of mist (EU-RAR (2005)). Since a molecular weights of 10 hydrate (about 342) was as about twice as the anhydride (about 162). So it was converted to LC50 = about 0.2mg/L/4h, and it was set as Category 2.

Name: isopropyl 3-[[(ethylamino)methoxyphosphinothioyl]oxy]crotonate
Rationale for classification: If the lower one is taken among rat LC50 values of both sex in 4-hour inhalation toxicity study , they are LC50 = 3.02mg/L and LC50 = 3.3mg/L, respectively (drugs application materials). And it was set as Category 4 based on the lowest value LC50=3.02 mg/L..

Name: 4'-Hydroxyacetanilide
Rationale for classification: Classification not possible due to lack of data

Name: dioxathion
Rationale for classification: Since the saturated vapor pressures concentrations pressure of this product is 0.000115mg/L (6*10^(-7)ppm), it is thought that the inhalation study was done in mist. It was set as category 2 based on rat LC50 = 0.3495mg/L (ACGIH (2002)).

Name: Fenthion
Rationale for classification: It was classified into category 3 based on the lower value among rat LC50 = 1.2 and 0.8mg/L (Agricultural-Chemicalsd abstracts).

Name: ethion
Rationale for classification: There are rat LC50 (4 hours) value: 0.864mg/L (ACGIH, 2003) and 0.45mg/L (ACGIH, 2003, ATSDR, 2001). Adopting the lower value, it was set as Category 2

Name: N,N-Dimethyldodecan-1-ylamine
Rationale for classification: Classification not possible due to lack of data

Name: Sodium 1-(methoxycarbonyl)pentadecane-1-sulfonate
Rationale for classification: Classification not possible due to lack of data

Name: 2-hydroxypropyl acrylate
Rationale for classification: Classification not possible due to lack of data

Name: 3-(3,4-dichlorophenyl)-1-methoxy-1-methylurea
Rationale for classification: Based on the rat LC50 (inhalation route) value of >5.0mg/L, together with the absence of mortality (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1993)).

Name: Zinc bis(N,N'-dimethyldithiocarbamate)
Rationale for classification: Because the rat LC50 (inhalation of vapour) values of 0.07mg/L (4 hours) (IUCLID (2000)) and 0.081mg/L (4 hours) (IUCLID (2000)) exceeded 90% of the saturated vapour concentration of 9.9*10^(-6)ppm under a saturated vapour pressure of 7.5*10^(-9)mmHg (extrapolation) [equivalent to 1.0*10^(-6)Pa (extrapolation)] (SRC (2006)), the substance was considered as "mist exposure" and was classified as Category 2.

Name: 1,3,5-trioxan
Rationale for classification: Classification not possible due to lack of data

Name: (E)-3-(dimethylamino)-1-methyl-3-oxoprop-1-enyl dimethyl phosphate
Rationale for classification: Calculation was done based on rat LC50 (4 hours) value: 0.09mg/L (ACGIH, 2002) and LC50 (1 hour) value: 0.61-0.91mg/L (4-hour equivalent 0.15-0.23mg/L) (ACGIH, 2002). Since the calculated values were 0.09mg/L, they were set to category 2.

Name: N-(4-tert-Butylbenzyl)-4-chloro-3-ethyl-1-methylpyrazole-5-carboxamide; Tebufenpyrad
Rationale for classification: Based on the rat LC50 (inhalation route) value of 2.7mg/L (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1993)).

Name: 2-chloro-2',6'-diethyl-N-(methoxymethyl)acetanilide
Rationale for classification: Classification cannot be determined, though the available rat inhalation study reported the LC50 value of >1.040mg/L, together with the absence of mortality (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1998)).

Name: N-methylformamide
Rationale for classification: Saturated vapor pressure level at 20degCis 223 ppm. It is written in GESTIS (Access on Feb.2008) of Priority 3 that there was no mortality and no clinical symptom in case those rats were exposed to 4.02 mg/L for 4 hours. The mist and dust standard value of Category 4 is 5 mg/L, and classification is not possible.

Name: Nitric acid
Rationale for classification: Nitric acid did not exist as steam and gas, and it considered that all the data of LC50 was mist. Since all of five data were within the range of 0.05 - 0.5mg/L, it was set as Category 2.

Name: tetrasodium 3,3'-[(3,3'-dimethyl[1,1'-biphenyl]-4,4'-diyl)bis(azo)]bis[5-amino-4-hydroxynaphthalene-2,7-disulphonate]
Rationale for classification: There is description that death was not acknowledged by rat 1-hour exposure (4-hour equivalent 0.1184mg/L) in the 0.4735mg/L concentration (HSDB (2006)). But there is no other data and the category could not be specified. Therefore, it cannot be classified since data is insufficient.

Name: 1,3,5-Trimethylbenzene
Rationale for classification: Because the rat LC50 value of 4,900ppm, calculated from the testing data of rat LC50 (inhalation of mist) of 24mg/L (4 hours) (CERI Hazard Data 2001-51 (2002)), exceeded the saturated vapour concentration (3,300ppm) under a saturated vapour pressure of 330Pa (25degC) (CERI Hazard Data 2001-51 (2002)), the substance was considered as "mist exposure" and was classified based on standard values expressed in mg/L.

Name: Aniline, 2-methoxy-
Rationale for classification: As aerosol, it is rat LC50 >3.87mg/L (EU-RAR (2002)). Since Category could not be specificked, it presupposed it cannot classify.

Name: 1,2-Bis(2-chlorophenyl)hydrazine
Rationale for classification: Classification not possible due to lack of data

Name: alpha-cyano-3-phenoxybenzyl 2,2-dichloro-1-(4-ethoxyphenyl)cyclopropanecarboxylate
Rationale for classification: Classification cannot be determined, though the available rat inhalation study reported the LC50 value of >1.5mg/L (4 hours) (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1983)).

Name: Carboxylic acids(higher fatty acids) barium salts
diphacinone
Rationale for classification: The saturated vapor pressure concentrations calculated from this substance's steam pressure 1.37*10^(-5)mPa (25degC) is 1.35*10^(-7)mg/L, and each concentration (2mg/L, 6ug/L) used for the inhalation study is considered to be a dust. Therefore, it was classified into category 1 based on higher toxic value LC50 <6ug/L/4 hr (HSDB (2003)) among rat LC50 values.

Name: polybrominated biphenyl
Rationale for classification: Based on the report that there is no mortality (EHC 152 (1994)) by 71 and 200mg/L (1h) (converted value for 4 hours are 17.8 and 50mg/L, respectively) in rats, it was set as the outside of Category.

Name: Decanoic acid
Rationale for classification: Classification not possible due to lack of data

Name: O-3,5,6-trichloro-2-pyridyl O,O-dimethyl phosphorothioate
Rationale for classification: Classification cannot be determined, though the available rat inhalation studies reported the LC50 values of >0.031mg/L and >0.67mg/L (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1989, 2005)).

Name: N-(1,3-Dimethylbutyl)-N'-phenyl-1,4-phenylenediamine
Rationale for classification: Classification not possible due to lack of data

Name: (1,3-Dioxo-4,5,6,7-tetrahydroisoindolin-2-yl)methyl 2,2-dimethyl-3-(2-methylprop-1-en-1-yl)cyclopropane-1-carboxylate
Rationale for classification: This substance is a solid whose saturated vapor pressure level (30degC)is 1.26*10^-5 mg/L. Since LC50 value of 3-hour inhalation exposure test employing rats is >2.74 mg/L (HSDB (2001)), the dust standard is applied. Since 4-hour equivalent LC50 value is >2.06 mg/L, classification cannot be specified, and classification is not possible.

Name: Sodium nitrite
Rationale for classification: Category 1 because of "SPECIES: Rat; ENDPOINT: LC50; VALUE: 0.0055mg/L/4H; VALUE: 5.5mg/m3/4H" (RTECS, 2004)

Name: 3',4'-dichloropropionanilide
Rationale for classification: Classification cannot be determined, though the available rat inhalation study reported the LC50 value of >1.24mg/L (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1989)).

Name: Pyrethrins and Pyrethroids
Rationale for classification: Category 4 because of "SPECIES: Rat; ENDPOINT: LC50(4hr.); VALUE: 3.4mg/L"(ATSDR, 2003)

Name: Molybdenum
Rationale for classification: Based on the description that change of the state was not admitted even if it done exposure to rats by the concentration of 25-30mg/L for 1 hour (the 4-hour equivalent of 25mg/L is 6.3mg/L) (ACGIH (2003), CERI Hazard Data (2002)), it was set as outside of category.

Name: 1-vinyl-2-pyrrolidone
Rationale for classification: Based on saturated vapor pressure level 12 Pa (EU-RAR (2003)) at 20degC, saturated vapor pressure at 20degC is 0.54 mg/L, and it was classified into Category 4 based on the report that LC50 value (4 hours) of rats was 3.07 mg/L (NICNAS (2000)). In addition, EU-Annex I, which is Xn; R20/21/22-48/20, is equivalent to the GHS Category 3 to 4.

Name: 2',4-Dichloro-alpha,alpha,alpha-trifluoro-4'-nitro-m-toluenesulfonanilide; Flusulfamide
Rationale for classification: Based on the dog LC50 (4 hour inhalation) value of 0.079mg/L (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1990)).

Name: cartap hydrochloride
Rationale for classification: It was set as Category 4 based on rat LC50 = 3.5mg/L/4H (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (non-submitted)).

Name: [(2-chlorophenyl)methylene]malononitrile
Rationale for classification: Since particulate aerosol inhalation LC50 of rat was 0.5 or less in 4-hour translation, it was set as Category 2.

Name: 2-(4-tert-butylphenoxy)cyclohexyl 2-propynyl sulfite
Rationale for classification: Classification cannot be determined, though the available rat inhalation study reported the LC50 value of >0.625mg/L (4 hours) (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (2005)).

Name: Fentin hydroxide
Rationale for classification: It was set as Category 2 based on rat inhalation LC50 = 0.06mg/L/4H (JMPR 827, 1991).

Name: 1,2-Dichloro-4-nitrobenzene
Rationale for classification: Classification not possible due to lack of data

Name: m-Phenylene-bis(methylamine)
Rationale for classification: Based on rat LC50 (1 hour) value: 3.75mg/L (4-hour equivalent 0.938mg/L) (ACGIH 7th, 2001) and LC50 (4 hours) value: 0.8mg/L (SIDS, 2001), it was set as Category 3.

Name: Triglycidyl isocyanurate
Rationale for classification: It was set as Category 3 based on rat inhalation (dust) LC50 = 650mg/m3 (CICAD 8 (1998)).

Name: bis(2-chloro-1-methylethyl) ether
Rationale for classification: Based on 4-hour exposure rat LC50 = 12.8mg/L (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data) in the acute inhalation toxicity study (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data), it was set as the outside of Category.

Name: 2,3-dicyano-1,4-dithiaanthraquinone
Rationale for classification: Based on the rat LC50 (inhalation route) value of 1.82mg/L (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1975)).

Name: 2,4-Dimethylaniline
Rationale for classification: Saturated vapor pressure level of this substance (25degC)is 175 ppm (0.867 mg/L). Since LC50 value with 1.53 mg/L of the 4-hour inhalation exposure test employing rats (DFGOT vol.19 (1998)) was larger than saturated vapor pressure level, it was classified into Category 4 by applying the mist standard.

Name: Hexanoic acid, 2-ethyl-
Rationale for classification: It is a liquid whose saturated vapor pressure level at 20degC is 0.23 mg/L.. Since it is written that there was no mortality even if rats were exposed to 2.36 mg/L for 6 hours in the 6-hour inhalation exposure test employing rats (Patty (5th, 2001)), 4-hour equivalent LC50 value is >3.54 mg/L. when applying the mist standard. Since classification cannot be specified, classification is not possible.

Name: 1-Amino-9,10-anthraquinone
Rationale for classification: Classification not possible due to lack of data

Name: Stannane, tributylfluoro-
Rationale for classification: It was set as Category 2 based on rat inhalation LC50 value of 0.4ppm/4H (= 0.00504mg/L) (ACGIH 7th, 2001).

Name: Methomyl
Rationale for classification: Based on 25% wettable powder rat (male) LC50 (1 hour) value: 1.99mg/L (4-hour equivalent 0.498mg/L), and 35.56% liquid medicine rat (female) LC50 (1 hour) value: 0.61mg/L (4-hour equivalent 0.15mg/L) (all are agricultural-chemicals abstracts), the lower value was adopted and it was set as Category 2.

Name: fensulfothion
Rationale for classification: The saturated vapor pressures concentrations pressure of this product is 0.0663ppm (0.00084mg/L), and it is thought that the inhalation study was done in mist. It was set as Category 1 based on LC50 = 0.0283mg/L calculated from eight data of rat LC50 value (ACGIH (2001), PATTY (5th, 2001), PD No.44 (1980), JMPR 239 (1972)).

Name: N,N'-(3,3'-Dichlorobiphenyl-4,4'-diyl)diammonium dichloride
Rationale for classification: Classification not possible due to lack of data

Name: 4-Methyl-1,3-phenylene diisocyanate
Rationale for classification: Based on the LC50 value (4 hours) of 897ppm, calculated from the testing data of rat LC50 (6 hour inhalation of dust/mist) of 4.27mg/L (PATTY 4th, 2000), exceeded the saturated vapor concentration (660 ppm) under a saturated vapour pressure of 67 Pa (25degC) (CERI Hazard Data 97-20, 1998), the substance is likely to contain mist, despite its description as vapour.

Name: 2-Cyclohexen-1-one, 3,5,5-trimethyl-
Rationale for classification: It done by higher concentrations than the saturated vapor pressure pressures concentrations, and based on LC50 = 7mg/L (SIDS (2003)) of the rat inhalation test considered to be mist tests. So it was set as Category 5

Name: Manganese N,N'-ethylenebis(dithiocarbamate)
Rationale for classification: Based on the rat LC50 (inhalation route) value of 7.38mg/L (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (2005)).

Name: 2,3-Dibromopropan-1-ol
Rationale for classification: Saturated vapor pressure level at 25degCis 118.4 ppm (1.06 mg/L). Since LC50 value with 9.92 mg/L of the 4-hour inhalation exposure test employing rats (RTECS (2008)) was larger than saturated vapor pressure level, it was classified into "Not classified" by applying the dust and mist standard. In addition, the EU classification is R20/22 (EU-Annex I).

Name: disul
Rationale for classification: Classification not possible due to lack of data

Name: Methyl 3-(4-methoxy-6-methyl-1,3,5-triazin-2-ylcarbamoylsulfamoyl)-2-thenoate
Rationale for classification: Based on the rat LC50 (inhalation route) value of >7.9mg/L (4 hours), together with the absence of mortality (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1997)).

Name: butyl (R)-2-[4-(4-cyano-2-fluorophenoxy)phenoxy]propionate
Rationale for classification: Based on the rat LC50 (inhalation route) value of >5.0mg/L (4 hours), together with the absence of mortality (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1995)).

Name: 1,2,4-triazole
Rationale for classification: Classification not possible due to lack of data

Name: Formamide
Rationale for classification: From description that a toxic phenomena was not acknowledged in 3900ppm of 6-hour exposure (4-hour equivalent 10.75mg/L) in the inhalation exposure test of the mist using the rat (ACGIH (7th, 2001)), it was set as the outside of Category.

Name: 2,4-Di-tert-butylphenol
Rationale for classification: Classification not possible due to lack of data

Name: Isodecanol
Rationale for classification: Saturated vapor pressure level of this substance (20degC)is 14.8 ppm (0.096 mg/L). Since there was no mortality with 95 ppm in the 6-hour inhalation exposure test employing rats, mice, and guinea pig (Patty (5th, 2001)), the mist standard is applied. Since the 4-hour equivalent is 0.93 mg/L, LC50 value is presumed to be >0.93 mg/L, however, the classification cannot be specified, and classification is not possible.

Name: 2-Methylnaphthalene
Rationale for classification: Classification not possible due to lack of data

Name: Aniline, N-(1-methylethyl)-
Rationale for classification: Category 4 because of "SPECIES: Rat (aspiration); ENDPOINT: LC50 = 1.2 mg/L /4H" (ACGIH, 2001)

Name: Distillates (petroleum), solvent-refined heavy paraffinic; Distillates (petroleum), solvent-refined light naphthenic; Lubricating oils (petroleum), C15-30, hydrotreated neutral oil-based; Lubricating oils (petroleum), C20-50, hydrotreated neutral oil-based; Petroleum; Paraffin oils
Rationale for classification: Category 4 because of "SPECIES: Rat;  ENDPOINT: LC50 = 2.18 mg/L." (IUCLID, 2000)

Name: O-2,4-dichlorophenyl O-ethyl S-propyl phosphorodithioate
Rationale for classification: Classification cannot be determined, though the available rat inhalation study reported the LC50 value of >2.7mg/L (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1988)).

Name: Potassium dichromate
Rationale for classification: Based on the rat LC50 (inhalation of dust/mist) of 0.099mg/L (EU-RAR No.53 (2005)).

Name: Sodium cyanate
Rationale for classification: Classification not possible due to lack of data

Name: fthalide
Rationale for classification: Rat LC50 (4 hours) value is >4.1mg/L (Agricultural-Chemicals abstracts). But the category could not be specified only by this data, it cannot be classified since data is insufficient.

Name: Benzoyl peroxide
Rationale for classification: Not classified because of "SPECIES: Rat; ENDPOINT: LC50>19.0mg/L" (SIDS,2002)

Name: Acetic acid
Rationale for classification: The saturated vapor pressures concentrations pressure of acetates is 20800ppm, and it is presumed that the inhalation study is done in the state of steam. Therefore, there is no data about mists, it cannot classify.

Name: Methyl isothiocyanate
Rationale for classification: Based on the rat LC50 (inhalation of dust) value of 0.48mg/L (4 hours) (HSDB (2006)).

Name: naled
Rationale for classification: Category 2 because of SPECIES: Rat; ENDPOINT: LC50(4hr.); VALUE: 0.19mg/L

Name: 2-butanone oxime
Rationale for classification: Saturated vapor pressure level (20degC) is 0.076 mg/L. LC50 value of the inhalation administration test employing rats is 20 mg/L / 4hr (IUCLID (2000)). Since the standard value of Category 4 is 0.05 mg/L according to the mist standard, it was classified into "Not classified".

Name: O-ethyl O-(4-methylthiophenyl) S-propyl dithiophosphate
Rationale for classification: There is no data and it cannot classify. (There is a data of mouse and hamster LC50 >0.49mg/L/4H (PATTY (5th, 2001)), and Category 3 and 4 can be assumed. )

Name: Glutaraldehyde
Rationale for classification: Category 2 because of ENDPOINT: LC50; VALUE (lower): 0.48 mg/L

Name: N-[2-[1-(4-Chlorophenyl)-1H-pyrazole-3-yloxymethyl]phenyl]-N-methoxycarbamic acid methyl ester
Rationale for classification: It was set as Category 3 based on rat LC50 = 0.58mg/L. (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data) that was a result of the inhalation study done by melting to a solvent in order to make it a diameter which can be inhaled.

Name: Lithium hydroxide monohydrate
Rationale for classification: Category 3 because of SPECIES: Rat; ENDPOINT: LC50; VALUE: 0.96mg/L/4H

Name: O-Ethyl O-2-(isopropoxycarbonyl)phenyl N-isopropylphosphoramidothioate; Isofenphos
Rationale for classification: Based on the LC50 value of 0.144mg/L calculated from the testing data of rat LC50 (inhalation of dust/mist) of 0.144mg/L (4 hours) (RTECS (2006)), 0.2mg/L (4 hours) (IUCLID (2000)) and 0.3mg/L (4 hours) (HSDB (2006)).

Name: Chloroethylene; Vinyl chloride
Rationale for classification: Due to the fact that the substance is "gas" according to the GHS definition and inhalation of its dust/mist is not expected.

Name: dinocap
Rationale for classification: It was set as category 2 based on rat LC50 (4h) = 0.36mg/L (RTECS (2003)). In addition, it is presumed that the saturated concentration of this product is very low, and the inhalation test is done in mist conditions.

Name: 1,8-dinitronaphthalene
Rationale for classification: Classification not possible due to lack of data

Name: O-2,4-Dichlorophenyl O,O-diethyl phosphorothioate; Dichlofenthion; ECP
Rationale for classification: Based on the rat LC50 (inhalation route) value of 1.75mg/L (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1994)).

Name: hexamethylphosphoric triamide
Rationale for classification: Classification not possible due to lack of data

Name: 1-[(6-Chloro-3-pyridyl)methyl]imidazolidine-2-(N-nitro)imine
Rationale for classification: There was an examination of a rat Agricultural Chemical Registration Data. But it cannot be classified since LC50 value is not acquired.

Name: carbendazim(ISO)
Rationale for classification: Due to insufficient data, classification is not possible. It is written in EHC149 (1993) that rat LC50 value is >5 mg/L in the test employing the dust, and it is unknown whether or not there is mortality. Therefore, although it was not classified into Category 4, suitability of Category 5 cannot be judged.

Name: Nonan-1-ol
Rationale for classification: Saturated vapor pressure level at 25degCis 0.18 mg/L.. Since LC50 value of 2-hour inhalation exposure test employing mice is 5,500 mg/m3 (the 6th volume (2008) of the MOE Risk Assessment, Patty (5th, 2001)), the mist standard is applied. 4-hour equivalent LC50 value is 2.75 mg/L, and it was classified into Category 4 by applying the mist standard.

Name: Diethyl sulfate
Rationale for classification: There is description that the example of all six rats died within 14 days by 500ppm 4-hour exposure (equivalent 3.15 mg/L) in the inhalation exposure test (DFGOT (vol.20, 2003)). But there was no other exposure data in mists and the category could not be specified only by this data. Therefore, it cannot be classified since data is insufficient.

Name: alpha-cyano-3-phenoxybenzyl 2,2-dimethyl-3-(1,2,2,2-tetrabromoethyl)cyclopropanecarboxylate
Rationale for classification: Male and female rat LC50 was >0.286mg/L in the inhalation exposure test (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data). And LC50 value was not calculated, it cannot be classified.

Name: 1,1'-Dimethyl-4,4'-bipyridinium salts (except paraquat dichloride)
Rationale for classification:
Based on the LD 50 value of 0.005mg/L calculated from the testing data of rat LC50 (6-hour inhalation of dust) of 0.001mg/L, 0.01mg/L, 0.01mg/L and 0.006mg/L (EHC 39 (1984)).
Note: Classified using data on Cl salts

Name: N'-(4-chloro-o-tolyl)-N,N-dimethylformamidine monohydrochloride
Rationale for classification: There is only a data with rat inhalation LC50 (1hr) value: >5.8mg/L (JMPR206 (1972)) (4-hour equivalent, in the case of steam: >2.9mg/L, and in case of mist and particulate: >1.45mg/L), and it cannot be classified since data is insufficient.

Name: Phosphoric acid, 2,2-dichloroethenyl dimethyl ester, compd. with calcium bis(2,2-dichloroethenyl methyl phosphate) (2:1)
2,2,2-trichloro-1,1-bis(4-chlorophenyl)ethanol
Rationale for classification: Based on the rat LC50 (inhalation route) value of >5.0mg/L (4 hours), together with the absence of mortality (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (2005)).

Name: 4-(2,4-dichlorobenzoyl)-1,3-dimethyl-5-pyrazolyl 4-toluenesulfonate
Rationale for classification: Based on the rat LC50 (inhalation route) value of 2.5mg/L (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1992)).

Name: Toluene, 3-nitro-
Rationale for classification: The category cannot be specified by only data that rat LC50 (1 hour) value: >2.417mg/L (4-hour equivalent 0.6043mg/L) ( IUCLID (2000), BUA 41 (1989)). And data is insufficient, it cannot be classified.

Name: ferbam
Rationale for classification: Category 2 because of "SPECIES: Rat; ENDPOINT: LC50(4hr.); VALUE: 0.4mg/L"(HSDB, 2006)

Name: Decan-1-ol
Rationale for classification: Saturated vapor pressure level of this substance (20degC)is 0.06 mg/L. Since LC50 value with 4 mg/L of the 2-hour inhalation exposure test employing mice (the 6th volume (2008) of the MOE Risk Assessment, IUCLID (2000)) is larger than saturated vapor pressure level, the mist standard is applied. Since 4-hour equivalent LC50 value is 2 mg/L, it was classified into Category 4.

Name: 2-chloro-2'-ethyl-N-(2-methoxy-1-methylethyl)-6'-methylacetanilide
Rationale for classification: Although no deaths were observed in rats receiving an inhalation dose of 1.75mg/L, there are no test data available for higher doses (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1986)).

Name: 1,1':2',1''-Terphenyl
Rationale for classification: This substance is a solid whose saturated vapor pressure level at 25degCis 0.003 mg/L. As a result of having investigated the cited reference (Toxicol.Appl.Pharmacol.1 (1959)) about an inhalation exposure test employing rats described in ACGIH (7th, 2001), it said that there were 4/8 mortality in the high concentration, and no mortality in the low concentration in the 1-hour inhalation exposure test by 2 concentrations (3.56 mg/L, 0.88 mg/L) employing male and female rats. Therefore, when LC50 value was judged to be 3.56 mg/L and the dust standard was applied, it was classified into Category 3 from 4-hour equivalent LC50 value with 0.89 mg/L. In addition, this cited reference covers Terphenyl which contains this substance as one of isomeric forms.

Name: Sodium alkyl(C16-18) sulfate
Rationale for classification: Classification not possible due to lack of data

Name: 2,2'-[oxybis(methylene)]bisoxirane
Rationale for classification: Based on rate LC50 (4 hours) value: 200ppm (equivalent 1.06mg/L) (ACGIH 7th, 2001, PATTY 4th, 1994), it was set as Category 4.

Name: 10H-Phenothiazine
Rationale for classification: Based on description that toxicity did not discover (IUCLID, 2000) by 1-hour exposure of 200 mg/L (4 hour exposure equivalent: 50mg/L) in rats, it was set as the outside of category.

Name: 3-(Methylsulfanyl)propanal
Rationale for classification: Classification not possible due to lack of data

Name: Endosulfan
Rationale for classification: Based on that both male rats LC50 = 0.0346mg/L and female LC50 = 0.0126mg/L (Agricultural-Chemicals abstracts) were in the scope of category 1, it was classified into category 1.

Name: Sodium chlorate
Rationale for classification: Since a both sex rat LC50 was >5mg/L (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data, 1990).

Name: S-4-phenoxybutyl N,N-dimethylthiocarbamate
Rationale for classification: Classification cannot be determined, though the available rat dermal study reported the LC50 value of >1.79mg/L (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1985)).

Name: alpha-cyano-3-phenoxybenzyl 2,2-dimethyl-3-(2-methylprop-1-enyl)cyclopropanecarboxylate
Rationale for classification: Since mouse LC50 (3h) = 570mg/m3 (0.43mg/L as a 4h conversion value) (poisonous and deleterious substances handling guide (Jiji Press Co., 2001)), it was set as category 2.

Name: Lindane
Rationale for classification: Category 4 because of "SPECIES: Rat; ENDPOINT: LC50(4hr.; VALUE: 1.6mg/L"(DFGOT vol.16, 2001; EHC 124, 1991)

Name: 2,2-dibromo-2-nitroethanol
Rationale for classification: Classification not possible due to lack of data

Name: Sulfuric acid, cadmium salt(1:1), hydrate (8/3)
Rationale for classification:
Data without.
(In the risk phrases of EU-Annex I (Access on Jun.2005) of cadmium sulfate (anhydride), it is supposed that inhalation toxicity is very high.)

Name: 2-methyl-N-[3-(1-methylethoxy)phenyl]benzamide
Rationale for classification: There is the data (Agricultural-Chemicals abstracts (1994)) of rat acuteness inhalation LC50 >1.32mg/L, it cannot be classified since data is insufficient.

Name: O,O-dimethyl phthalimidomethyl S-phosphorodithioate
Rationale for classification: Based on the lower one among rat inhalation LC50 (4 hours) = 0.054mg/L (RTECS (2003)) and LC50 (1 hour) = 2.76mg/L [4-hour conversion value 0.69mg/L] (HSDB (2003)), it was set as Category 2.

Name: Dipotassium hexafluorosilicate
Rationale for classification: Classified into R23 according to EU-Annex. But there was no inhalation medication examination for an animal. So it cannot classify since data is insufficient.

Name: barium oxide, obtained by calcining witherite
N,N-Dimethylaniline
Rationale for classification: There was no 50% lethal dose data in mist inhalation. But there is information that 40% died within four days from inhalation exposure of mist 1.88mg/L for 4 hours (DFGOT vol.3 (1991)), and it is thought that LC50 goes into 1.0 - 5.0mg/L.. It was set as Category 4.

Name: Chlordimeform
Rationale for classification: It was set as Category 4 based on rat inhalation LC50 (1hr) = 14.7mg/L (4-hour equivalent 4.35mg/L) (JMPR206 (1972)). In addition, the saturated concentration of this product is about 0.47ppm (3.7mg/m3) (20degC), and it is presumed that the inhalation study was done in mist conditions.

Name: 4-Chloro-3-methylphenol
Rationale for classification: Since there was no mortality with highest dose 0.704 mg/L in the dust inhalation exposure test employing rats (4 hours) (DFGOT vol.2 (1991)), LC50 value is considered to be >0.704 mg/L, however, classification is not possible since classification cannot be specified.

Name: 3-(3,5-Dichlorophenyl)-5-methyl-5-vinyl-1,3-oxazolidine-2,4-dione
Rationale for classification: It is a solid whose saturated vapor pressure level at 20degC is 1.8*10^-6 mg/L. Although LC50 value of the inhalation exposure test employing rats is >29.1 mg/L (JMPR (1995)), classification is not possible since exposure time is unknown.

Name: yttrium
Rationale for classification: Classification not possible due to lack of data

Name: Narasin
Rationale for classification: LC50 value cannot be specified from LC50 data ( >400mg/m3/30min) (RTECS (1996)). And it cannot be classified regardless of steam/mist.

Name: N-[4-(p-Tolyloxy)benzyl]-1-methyl-3-ethyl-4-chloro-1H-pyrazole-5-carboxamide

Name: Bis(2-ethylhexyl) phthalate
Rationale for classification: Based on the rat LC50 (mist) of over 10.62 mg/L (EU-RAR No.42 (2003)).

Name: Stibine
Rationale for classification: Due to the fact that the substance is "gas" according to the GHS definition and inhalation of its dust/mist is not expected.

Name: 1-(4-biphenylyloxy)-3,3-dimethyl-1-(1H-1,2,4-triazol-1-yl)-2-butanol
Rationale for classification: Classification cannot be determined, though the available rat inhalation study reported the LC50 value of >0.55mg/L (4 hours) (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1984)).

Name: dinitrophenol
Rationale for classification: Data without. In addition, HSDB (2003) has a statement that the inhalation toxicity of dust is high, and ATSDR (1995) has the death report of humans in 40mg/m3 (there is possibility of chronic exposure).

Name: Toxaphene
Rationale for classification: Particulate inhalation half fatal dose 3.4mg/L (1hr) of the rat (ATSDR (1986)) was converted into exposure for 4 hours to presume LC50: 0.85mg/L.. So it was set as Category 3.

Name: Hydrogenated terphenyl
Rationale for classification: This substance is a liquid whose saturated vapor pressure level at 25degC is 1.3 mg/L (128 ppm). Since LC50 value of 4-hour inhalation exposure test employing rats is >4.7 mg/L (ACGIH (7th, 2001)), and LC50 value of 4-hour aerosol inhalation exposure test employing rats (OECD TG 403, GLP) is >4.3 mg/L (IUCLID (2000)), and any of them are over saturated vapor pressure level, the mist standard was applied, however, classification cannot be specified, classification is not possible.

Name: Zinc stearate
Rationale for classification: The saturated vapor pressures concentrations pressure of this product is a value near 0, and it is thought that the inhalation study was done with the dust. Based on rat LC50 >50mg/L (EU-RAR (2004)), it was set as the outside of Category.

Name: 2-Methoxyethyl acetate; Ethylene glycol monomethyl ether acetate
Rosin
Rationale for classification: Based on rat LC50 (6 hours) value: about 1.5mg/L (4 hour equivalent: about 2.3mg/L) (IUCLID, 2000).it was set as Category 4.

Name: Hydrochloric acid
Rationale for classification: Rat LC50 = 1.68mg/L / 1h is the aerosol data (SIDS (2002)). It was set as category 2 based on 4-hour value 0.42mg/L of this value.

Name: Zinc chloride
Rationale for classification: LC50 value decided for the animal is not acquired. But the humans deaths after exposure is reported though an exposure level was unknown (ACGIH (2001), PATTY (5th, 2001)). Therefore, it was set to category 1-5.

Name: Methyl 2-(4,6-dimethoxy-2-pyrimidinyloxy)-6-[1-(methoxyimino)ethyl]benzoate
Rationale for classification: Based on the rat LC50 (inhalation route) value of >5.5mg/L, together with the absence of mortality at this level (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1995)).

Name: 1,2,4-Trichlorobenzene
Rationale for classification: It is written that there was no adverse effect with 1,800 ppm (13.6 mg/L) in 7-hour inhalation exposure test employing rats (EU-RAR (2003)). When applying the mist standard from saturated vapor pressure level of this substance (25degC) with 2.9 mg/L, 4-hour equivalent LC50 value is considered to be >17.7 mg/L. Therefore, it was classified into "Not classified". In addition, it is also written in EU-RAR (2003) that there was no mortality in 4-hour inhalation exposure test with 418 ppm (3.1 mg/L) employing rats, and there was no symptom in 7.5-hour inhalation exposure test with 330 ppm (2.5 mg/L) employing rats (4 hour equivalent: 452 ppm (3.4 mg/L)).

Name: p-Chloroaniline
Rationale for classification: Based on the rat LC50 value of 448ppm, calculated from the testing data of rat LC50 (4-hour inhalation) of 2.34mg/L (MOE Risk Assessment vol. 2 (2003)) exceeded the saturated vapour concentration (20ppm) under a saturated vapour pressure of 2.0kPa (20degC), the substance was classified based on the mist/dust classification.

Name: Parathion
Rationale for classification: It is based on rat LC50 0.032mg/L (4hours) (a statistically calculated values, ACGIH (2003) others).

Name: phenylphosphine
Rationale for classification: Based on rat LC50 (4 hours) value: 38ppm (equivalent 0.17mg/L) (ACGIH 7th, 2001), it corresponds to category 1 when the test conditions was steam or stem including mist, and category 2 when the condition was mist. But whether it is steam or mist could not be judged from the acquired information. Therefore, it cannot be classified.

Name: 1,3-Butadiene
Rationale for classification: Due to the fact that the substance is "gas" according to the GHS definition and inhalation of its dust/mist is not expected.

Name: alpha-Cyano-3-phenoxybenzyl 2-(4-chlorophenyl)-3-methylbutyrate; Fenvalerate
Rationale for classification: Based on the rat LC50 (4 hour inhalation) value of 2.810mg/L (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1995)).

Name: 2,2'-((3,3',5,5'-tetramethyl-(1,1'-biphenyl)-4,4'-diyl)-bis(oxymethylene))-bis-oxirane
Rationale for classification: Classification not possible due to lack of data

Name: 2-chloro-N-(3-methoxy-2-thienyl)-2',6'-dimethylacetanilide
Rationale for classification: Based on the rat LC50 (inhalation route) value of >5.7mg/L, together with the absence of mortality (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1922)).

Name: Dimethyl 2,2-dichlorovinyl phosphate; Dichlorvos
Rationale for classification: Because the LC50 values of 50.3ppm, 38ppm, 72ppm, 57.9ppm and 49.4ppm, calculated respectively from the testing data of rat LC50 (1 hour) of 0.455mg/L (EHC 79 (1988)), LC50 (4 hours) of 0.34mg/L (EHC 79 (1988)), 0.65mg/L, 0.523mg/L and 0.447mg/L (PATTY (4th, 1999)), exceeded the saturated vapour concentration (20.9ppm) under a saturated vapour pressure of 0.0158mmHg (25degC; equivalent to 2.11Pa), the substance was considered as "mist exposure" and was classified based on the LC50 of 0.266mg/kg (4-hour inhalation of dust/mist).

Name: Dicyclohexan-1-yl phthalate
Rationale for classification: It is written that LC50 value of 1-hour inhalation exposure test employing rats is >3.2 mg/L (CERI/NITE Hazard Assessment Report (2008)). Since 4-hour equivalent LC50 value is >0.8 mg/L when applying the dust standard due to a solid, the classification cannot be specified, and classification is not possible.

Name: Coplymer of alkyl(c=8) acrylate,methyl methacrylate and tributyltin methacrylate
paraquat-dimethylsulfate
Rationale for classification: It was set as Category 1 since all three data (ACGIH (2001), EHC 39 (1984)) were 0.05mg/L or less except the time when dust sizes is large.

Name: Anthracene
Rationale for classification: Classification not possible due to lack of data

Name: S-benzyl N-(1,2-dimethylpropyl)-N-ethylthiocarbamate
Rationale for classification: Classification cannot be determined, though the available rat dermal study reported the LC50 value of >4.06mg/L (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1984)).

Name: 2-chloro-2',6'-diethyl-N-(2-propoxyethyl)acetanilide
Rationale for classification: The available rat inhalation studies reported the LC50 value of >2.8mg/L, but there are no test data available for higher doses (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1983)).

Name: Phthalic anhydride
Rationale for classification: Because the rat LC50 (inhalation) value of >0.21mg/L (34ppm when the conversion factor of 1ppm = 6.16mg/m3 (20degC) was applied) (MOE Risk Assessment vol. 2 (2003)) exceeded the saturated vapour concentration (0.03ppm) under a saturated vapour pressure of 0.0003hPa (20degC), the substance was considered as "dust exposure." However, classification is not possible since the LC50 of >0.21mg/L is not a fixed value.

Name: sulfotep
Rationale for classification: Since the saturated vapor pressures concentrations pressure of this product is 0.2ppm, it is thought that the inhalation experiments was conducted in mist conditions. Based on LC50 = 0.038mg/L which is lower value among two rat data (ACGIH (2005), DFGOT vol.13 (1999), PATTY (5th, 2001)), it was set as Category 1.

Name: 4-aminoazobenzene
Rationale for classification: There was description that death was not acknowledged by rat 4-hour exposure of 2.8mg/L in the inhalation exposure test (BUA 217 (2000)). But there is no data in the concentration beyond this, and it cannot classify since data is insufficient for carrying out the outside of Category.

Name: bis(2-methoxyethyl)ether

Name: Tetrafluoroethylene
