Name: o-Chlorotoluene
Rationale for classification: Because the rat LC50 value of 7,119ppm (SIDS (2004)) exceeded the saturated vapour concentration (4,510ppm) under a saturated vapour pressure of 456Pa (25degC), the substance was considered as "mist exposure."

Name: 2-[4-(2,4-dichlorobenzoyl)-1,3-dimethyl-5-pyrazolyloxy]acetophenone
Rationale for classification: Classification cannot be determined, though the available rat inhalation study reported the LC50 value of >0.28mg/L (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1984)).

Name: 3-Chloro-2-methylprop-1-ene
Rationale for classification: Classification not possible due to lack of data

Name: 2-Heptanone
Rationale for classification: There is the description that the all three rat died from 5100ppm (equivalent 23.8mg/L) within 4 hours in the inhalation exposure test (PATTY (4th, 1994)). But there is no other data. Therefore, it cannot be classified since data is insufficient for specifying category.

Name: alpha-cyano-3-phenoxybenzyl N-(2-chloro-alpha,alpha,alpha-trifluoro-p-tolyl)-D-valinate
Rationale for classification: Based on the rat LC50 (inhalation route) value of 0.44mg/L (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1988)).

Name: monocrotophos
Rationale for classification: Calculated based on rat LC50 (4 hours) value: 0.063mg/L and 0.1mg/L (ACGIH, 2002), and LC50 (1 hour) value:0.163mg/L (4-hour equivalent 0.0408mg/L) (ACGIH, 2002). The calculation value was lower than these lowest value. And 0.0408 mg/L of lowest value was adopted and set it to category 1.

Name: Fluorine
Rationale for classification: Due to the fact that the substance is "gas" according to the GHS definition and inhalation of its dust/mist is not expected.

Name: (5-Benzyl-3-furyl)methyl 2,2-dimethyl-3-(2-methylprop-1-en-1-yl)cyclopropanecarboxylate
Rationale for classification: It is written that LC50 value of 4-hour aerosol inhalation exposure test employing rats is >9.49 mg/L, and LC50 value of 1-hour aerosol inhalation exposure test employing rats is >12.0 mg/L (4-hour equivalent: >4.9 mg/L) (EHC 92 (1989)). Since LC50 value was >9.49 mg/L, it was classified into "Not classified".

Name: thiacloprid
Rationale for classification: It was set as category 4 based on that the female rat LC50 of the inhalation exposure examination is about 1.223mg/L (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data).

Name: Ethyl 2-[(dimethoxyphosphinothioyl)thio]-2-phenylacetate; Phenthoate; PAP
Rationale for classification: Based on the rat LC50 (inhalation route) value of 3.17mg/L (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1980)).

Name: Sodium dodecan-1-yl sulfate
Rationale for classification: Classification not possible due to lack of data

Name: bis(8-quinolinolato)copper
Rationale for classification: Classification cannot be determined, though the available rat inhalation study reported the LC50 value of >0.94mg/L (4 hours) (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1989)).

Name: (Z)-2'-methylacetophenone 4,6-dimethyl-2-pyrimidinylhydrazone
Rationale for classification: Classification cannot be determined, though the available rat inhalation study reported the LC50 value of >3.8mg/L (4 hours) (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1991)).

Name: 2-(Diethylamino)ethyl methacrylate
Rationale for classification: Based on the guinea pig LC50 value of 1,500ppm, calculated from the testing data of guinea pig LC50 (4 hour inhalation of vapour) of 11mg/L (CERI Hazard Data 2001-64 (2002)), exceeded the saturated vapour concentration (140ppm) under a saturated vapour pressure of 0.014kPa (25degC) (HSDB (2006)), the substance was considered as "mist exposure," and  the obtained LC50 was lower than the upper limit value of Category 4 (5mg/L) by more than 2.5 fold.

Name: Ammonium nitrate
Rationale for classification: Not classified because of "SPECIES: Rat; ENDPOINT: LC50(4hr.; VALUE: >88.8mg/L"(IUCLID, 2000)

Name: Diazinon
Rationale for classification: It was set as Category 4 based on Rat LC50 (4 hours) value: 3.1mg/L (Agricultural-Chemicals abstracts).

Name: 4-Nitrotoluene
Rationale for classification: There is the description that rat LC50 (1 hour) value: >758ppm (4-hour corresponding values 1.06mg/L) (CERI Hazard Data (2000)), and that death was not acknowledged in the test which used rats by 1-hour exposure of 4.167mg/L (4-hour corresponding values 1.042mg/L) and 4-hour exposure of 152ppm  (corresponding values 0.851mg/L) (SIDS (2005)). But the category could not be specified from these data. Therefore, it cannot be classified since data is insufficient.

Name: O,O-dimethyl-4-oxobenzotriazin-3-ylmethyl phosphorodithioate
Rationale for classification: Based on level LC50 = 0.126mg/L obtained by statistics calculation of six data of rat inhalation LC50 (4hr) level (PATTY (5th, 2001), JMPR 818 (1991), ACGIH (2002)), it was classified into category 2.

Name: Pentachloronitrobenzene
Rationale for classification: There is a possibility of being in category 4, category 5, or outside of category from the data of rat LC50 (4-hour exposure): >1.7mg/L. But it cannot be classified since the category can not to be specified.

Name: 1,3-diphenylguanidine
Rationale for classification: Classification not possible due to lack of data

Name: 1-Chloro-2-(chloromethyl)benzene
Rationale for classification: Since LC50 value of 4-hour aerosol inhalation exposure test employing rats (OECD TG 403, GLP)is 2.8 mg/L (SIDS (2004)), it was classified into Category 4.

Name: 1,1-Dimethyl-4,4-bipyridinium dichloride
Rationale for classification: It was set as Category 1 rat  LC50 = 0.00084mg/L (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1991)).

Name: O,O-Diethyl O-2-quinoxalinyl phosphorothioate; Quinalphos
Rationale for classification: Based on the rat LC50 (inhalation route) value of 0.45mg/L (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1983)).

Name: 4-Methylideneoxetan-2-one
Rationale for classification: Classification not possible due to lack of data

Name: Diboron trioxide
Rationale for classification: Since most vapor pressure of this product can be disregarded, it is thought that the inhalation study was done with the dust. There was no study in which LC50 was obtained. So data was insufficient, it cannot be classified.

Name: Diuron
Rationale for classification: According to Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1996) of the rat LC50 >5.0mg/L, it was set as the outside of Category.

Name: Di-n-butyl phthalate
Rationale for classification: Based on the rat LD50 (mist) of over 15.68 mg/L (EU-RAR No.29 (2003)).

Name: Mixture of 2,4-dinitro-6-octylphenyl crotonate and 2,6-dinitro-4-octylphenyl crotonate (octyl=1-methylheptyl,1-ethylhexyl,1-propylpentyl); Dinocap; DPC
6-methyl-1,3-dithiolo[4,5-b]quinoxalin-2-one
Rationale for classification: Based on the rat LC50 (inhalation route) value of 2.16mg/L (4 hours) (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data).

Name: Metribuzin
Rationale for classification: It is female rats LC50 >0.86mg/L (Agricultural-Chemicals abstracts), and cannot be classified.

Name: 2,2'-{Isopropylidenebis[(2,6-dibromo-4,1-phenylene)oxy]}diethanol
Rationale for classification: Due to the absence of fixed value, although the substance can be classified as Category 4 or Not classified, based on the LC50 value (4 hour) of >3.1ppm, calculated from the testing data of rat LC50 (1-hour inhalation of dust) of over 12.5 mg/L (EHC 172 1995).

Name: 2,3-Dihydro-2,2-dimethyl-7-benzo[b]furyl N-(dibutylamino)thio-N-methylcarbamate; Carbosulfan
Rationale for classification: Based on the rat LC50 (inhalation exposure) value of 0.15mg/L (4 hours) (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1981)).

Name: O-3-tert-butylphenyl N-(6-methoxy-2-pyridyl)-N-methylthiocarbamate
Rationale for classification: Based on the rat LC50 (inhalation route) value of >6.52mg/L (4 hours), together with the absence of mortality (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1988)).

Name: S-(2,3-Dihydro-5-methoxy-2-oxo-1,3,4-thiadiazol-3-yl)methyl O,O-dimethyl phosphorodithioate; Methidathion; DMTP
Rationale for classification: Based on the rat LC50 (inhalation exposure) value of 0.109mg/L representing the lower of the two testing data, 0.109mg/L and 0.173mg/L (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data, 1993).

Name: Fenitrothion
Rationale for classification: Rat LC50 (4 hours) value was >2.210mg/L (Agricultural-Chemicals abstracts). But Category could not be specificked, it cannot classify since data is insufficient.

Name: Distillates (petroleum), solvent-refined heavy paraffinic; Distillates (petroleum), solvent-refined light naphthenic; Lubricating oils (petroleum), C15-30, hydrotreated neutral oil-based; Lubricating oils (petroleum), C20-50, hydrotreated neutral oil-based; Petroleum; Paraffin oils
Rationale for classification: Category 4 because of "SPECIES: Rat;  ENDPOINT: LC50 = 2.18 mg/L." (IUCLID, 2000)

Name: ethyl N-[2,3-dihydro-2,2-dimethylbenzofuran-7-yloxycarbonyl(methyl)aminothio]-N-isopropyl-beta-alaninate
Rationale for classification: It was set as Category 2 based on rat LC50 = 0.15mg/L (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data) in the inhalation exposure test (dust and mists).

Name: 1,3-Benzenediol
Rationale for classification: Based on rat LC50 value by 1 hour exposure: 21.3mg/L (4 hour equivalent: 5.33mg/L (IUCLID 2000)), it was set as Category 5.

Name: Copper monochloride
Rationale for classification: It was set as Category 3 based on mouse LC50 value 1.0mg/L (1008mg/m3) (RTECS, 2000) of an inhalation administration test.

Name: 2-tert-Butylimino-3-isopropyl-5-phenyltetrahydro-4H-1,3,5-thiadiazin-4-one; buprofezin
Rationale for classification: It was set as Category 4 based on LC50 value >4.57mg/L/4H using a rat of the inhalation exposure test (dust mists) (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (2001)).

Name: Titanium dioxide
Rationale for classification: Not classified because of "SPECIES: Rat;  LC>6.82mg/L/4h" (IUCLID, 2000)

Name: 2,2-Dibromo-2-cyanoacetamide
Rationale for classification: Saturated vapor pressure level of this substance (25degC)is 1.18 ppm (0.01 mg/L). Since LC50 value with 0.32 mg/L of the 4-hour inhalation exposure test employing rats (HSDB (2008)) was larger than saturated vapor pressure level, it was classified into Category 2 by applying the dust standard.

Name: Phosphoric acid
Rationale for classification: There was data that rat LC50 (1 hour) value was >0.85mg/L (4-hour equivalent >0.21mg/L) (RTECS (2006)). But the category could not be specified only by this data. Therefore, it cannot be classified since data is insufficient.

Name: Methanamine
Rationale for classification: Since it was gas on a GHS definition, it was classified into "Not applicable".

Name: lithium hydride
Rationale for classification: There is a report about the rat inhalation toxicity studies in which 2/10 died at 0.022mg/L/4H and 4/10 died (DFGOTvol.3 (1991)) at 0.036mg/L/7H (equivalent: 0.063mg/L/4H). And it is strongly expected that LC50 is 0.05 - 0.5mg/L/4H, it was set as category 2.

Name: Adipic acid
Rationale for classification: Since Saturated vapor pressure pressures concentrations is = 9.9ppm, it is thought that the inhalation study was done in mist. It was set as Category 5 based on rat LC50 = 7.7mg/L (CERI Hazard Data (1998)).

Name: 2-(4-ethoxyphenyl)-2-methylpropyl 3-phenoxybenzyl ether
Rationale for classification: Based on rat LC50 >5.9g/m3 = 5.9mg/L (4h) (Agricultural-Chemicals abstracts (1986)), it carried out the outside of Category.

Name: Monosodium sulfite
Rationale for classification: Classification not possible due to lack of data

Name: Diammonium peroxydisulfate
Rationale for classification: LC50 value of 4-hour inhalation exposure test employing rats (OECD TG 403, GLP) is >2.95 mg/L (SIDS (2005), NICNAS (2001), IUCLID (2000)). When applying the dust standard due to a solid, classification cannot be specified, classification is not possible.

Name: 1-(3,5-dichloro-2,4-difluorophenyl)-3-(2,6-difluorobenzoyl)urea
Rationale for classification: Based on the rat LC50 (inhalation route) value of >5.0mg/L (4 hours), together with the absence of mortality (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1996)).

Name: Chloromethane; Methyl chloride
Rationale for classification: Due to the fact that the substance is "gas" according to the GHS definition and inhalation of its dust/mist is not expected.

Name: Acetamide, N,N-dimethyl-
Rationale for classification: Saturated vapor pressure level at 25degC is 2631.58 ppm (9.38 mg/L). Since LC50 value with 10.01 mg/L (SIDS (2001)) of the 1-hour inhalation exposure test employing rats is larger than saturated vapor pressure level, 4-hour equivalent LC50 value is 2.50 mg/L when applying the mist standard, and it was classified into Category 4. In addition, EU classification is Xn; R20/21 (EU-Annex I), and is equivalent to Category 3-4.

Name: Biphenyl
Rationale for classification: There in only a data that mouse LC50 (4 hours) value: >43ppm (corresponding values 0.27mg/L) (CERI Hazard Data (1999), CICAD 6 (1999)), but the category could not be specified. Therefore, it cannot be classified since data is insufficient.

Name: Dimethyl carbamyl chloride
Rationale for classification: Classification not possible due to lack of data

Name: Demeton (mixed isomers)
Classification: Mixture:Category 1; O-:Classification not possible; S-:Classification not possible
Rationale for classification:
Since the this vapor saturated vapor pressure of the mixture: material is 0.297ppm (0.003mg/L), it is thought that the inhalation study was done in mist. It was set as Category 1 based on LC50 = 0.0439mg/L calculated from four data (ACGIH (2002), PATTY (5th, 2001)) of rat LC50 value.
O-body: datum without.
S-body: datum without.

Name: 2,2'-Iminodiethanol
Rationale for classification: The saturated vapor pressures concentrations pressure of this product is 0.37ppm. Mortality is not seen according to two rat acute toxicity tests (IUCLID (2000)) in saturated vapor pressure pressures concentrations. And LC50 level is not calculated, it cannot be classified.

Name: 2-Isopropylphenyl N-methylcarbamate; Isoprocarb; MIPC
Rationale for classification: Classification not possible since the acute toxicity value cannot be determined, though there was no evidence of death observed at the highest dose of 2.1mg/L in rat inhalation studies (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1995)).

Name: Bicyclo[2.2.1]hept-5-ene-2,3-dicarboxylic acid, 1,4,5,6,7,7-hexachloro-
Rationale for classification: There are the descriptions thet rat LC50 value in 4-hour exposure is >47.4ppm (equivalent 0.754mg/L) (CERI Hazard Data Description (2002)), and that death was not acknowledged in a rat by 4-hour exposure to 0.79mg/L (EHC 185 (1996)). It was not category 1. But there is no other data and the category could not be specified. Therefore, it cannot be classified since data is insufficient.

Name: N,N'-[1,1'-biphenyl]-4,4'-diylbisacetamide
Rationale for classification: Since there is no animal data, it cannot classify. In EU, it is R20 (hazardous if it is inhaled).

Name: endrin
Rationale for classification: There is description that 3-5 among 10 examples died from the mists and dust concentration of 2mg/L in the test which carried out exposure to the rat for 1 hour (4-hour equivalent 0.5 mg/L) (EHC 130 (1992), DFGOT (vol.18, 2002)). But there is no data of LC50 value. Therefore, it cannot be classified since the category cannot to be specified.

Name: Cadmium oxide
Rationale for classification: Based on the leathal dose of 0.011 mg/L calculated from the testing data of human leathal dose (4 hour exposure to cadmium oxide fume) of 0.01mg/L (ACGIH 7th, 2001), 0.012 mg/L (EHC 134, 1992) and 0.011 mg/L (EHC 134, 1992).

Name: Chlorotrifluoroethane
Rationale for classification: Due to the fact that the substance is "gas" according to the GHS definition and inhalation of its dust/mist is not expected.

Name: 2-Chloro-1,1,1,2-tetrafluoroethane; HCFC-124
Rationale for classification: Due to the fact that the substance is "gas" according to the GHS definition and inhalation of its dust/mist is not expected.

Name: Ethylenediamine
Rationale for classification: Based on an LC50 value (8 hours) of over 29 mg/L (SIDS (2003)) calculated from testing data of rat (inhalation of vapour). The LC50 value (4 hours equivalent) is calculated at over 58 mg/L. The saturated vapour concentration under a saturated vapor pressure of 1.7kPa (25degC) (SIDS (2003)) stands at 17,000 ppm, which is converted into 41 mg/L (1 ppm=2.46 mg/m3 (25degC)). The LC50 value calculated (over 58 mg/L) exceeds the saturated vapour concentration. The substance, under the test conditions, is considered "mist" and hence not classified according to the criteria for "particles and mist."

Name: Magnesium stearate
Rationale for classification: This product is a solid, and vapor pressures can be disregarded mostly. And it is thought that the inhalation study was done with the dust. Since data is insufficient, it cannot classify.

Name: bornan-2-one
Rationale for classification: There is a statement of rat LC50: 0.5mg/L (RTECS (2004)) and it was set to Category 2 when exposed for 4 hours. But it cannot be classified since there was no statement of time of exposure. (It is more desirable to be set as Category 2 from safety perspective, when there are necessities, such as a display.)

Name: Ethanol, 2-(1-methylethoxy)-
Rationale for classification: Saturated concentration is 6961ppm and it is guessed that each inhalation study is performed in the state of steam. Since there is no data about mists, it cannot be classified.

Name: 2,5-dichloroaniline
Rationale for classification: Classification is not possible because there is no data. In addition, EU classification of 3,4-Dichloroaniline (CAS No.95-76-1) which is a constitutional isomer is T;23/24/25 (EU-Annex I).

Name: fosthiazate
Rationale for classification: It was set as category 3 based on 4-hour exposure LC50 = 0.558mg/L (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data) of rat inhalation (mist).

Name: 1,2,3,6-tetrahydro-N-(trichloromethylthio)phthalimide
Rationale for classification: Based on male rats LC50 (4 hours) level: 0.72mg/L (Agricultural-Chemicals abstracts), it was set as Category 3.

Name: Dibromochloromethane
Rationale for classification: Classification not possible due to lack of data

Name: butyl lactate
Rationale for classification: Not classified because of SPECIES: Rat; ENDPOINT: LC50(4hr.; VALUE: >5.14mg/L(RTECS, 2005)

Name: N-propyl-N-[2-(2,4,6-trichlorophenoxy)ethyl]imidazole-1-carboxamide
Rationale for classification: Classification cannot be determined, though the available rat inhalation study reported the LC50 value of >2.16mg/L (4 hours) (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1996)).

Name: O-4-Bromo-2,5-dichlorophenyl O-methyl phenylphosphorothioate
Rationale for classification: It was set as Category 3 based on 0.9mg/kg/4H which is the lower value among the rat LC50 = 0.9 and 1.65mg/kg/4H of JMPR (WHO Pesticide Residues Series 5, 1975) in Priority 1 document.

Name: Thiram
Rationale for classification: There is description that rats survived even if they ware exposed to 0.5mg/L and 6.255mg/L for 4 hours (ACGIH (7th, 2001)). But there was no data on the lethal concentration, and category could not be specified. Therefore, it cannot classify since data is insufficient.

Name: Methane, isocyanato-
Rationale for classification: Saturated concentration is 459406ppm, and it is guessed that each inhalation study is done in the state of steam. Since there is no data about mists, it cannot be classified.

Name: 2,4-Dichloro-1-nitrobenzene
Rationale for classification: Classification not possible due to lack of data

Name: 2-Butanone, peroxide
Rationale for classification: Classification not possible due to lack of data

Name: Dipotassium peroxodisulphate
Rationale for classification: Since it is written that LC50 value of 1-hour inhalation exposure test employing rats is >42.9 mg/L (SIDS (2005), IUCLID (2000)), 4-hour equivalent LC50 value is >10.7 mg/L when applying the dust standard due to a solid. Therefore, it was classified into "Not classified".

Name: Diphenylmethane diisocyanate   (4,4'-M.D.I.)
Rationale for classification: Category 2 because of "SPECIES: Rat; ENDPOINT: LC50(4hr.; VALUE: 0.369mg/L"(ACGIH 7th, 2001)

Name: Dihydrogen selenide
Rationale for classification: Due to the fact that the substance is "gas" according to the GHS definition and inhalation of its dust/mist is not expected.

Name: cadmium distearate, pure
Rationale for classification: It was set as Category 2 based on rat LC50 = 0.13mg/L/2H (0.065mg/L/4H by 4-hour exchange) (RTECS, 2004).

Name: 4,4'-Diisocyanato-3,3'-dimethylbiphenyl
Rationale for classification: Classification not possible due to lack of data

Name: 3,5-dichloro-N-(1,1-dimethyl-2-propynyl)benzamide
Rationale for classification: Classification cannot be determined, though the available rat inhalation study reported the LC50 value of >2.1mg/L (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1994)).

Name: ethoprophos
Rationale for classification: Category 2 because of "SPECIES: Rat; ENDPOINT: LC50(4hr.); VALUE:0.250 mg/L"(JMPR 961, 1999)

Name: hexakis(2-methyl-2-phenylpropyl)distannoxane
Rationale for classification: Classification cannot be determined, though the available rat inhalation study reported the LC50 value of >1.83mg/L (4 hours) (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1987)).

Name: Propionic acid
Rationale for classification: Classification not possible due to lack of data

Name: N-(Cyclohexan-1-ylsulfanyl)phthalimide
Rationale for classification: Classification not possible due to lack of data

Name: S-Ethyl 2-(4-chloro-2-methylphenoxy)thioacetate; Phenothiol; MCPA-thioethyl
Rationale for classification: Classification not possible because the available rat inhalation LC50 of >0.044mg/L (the upper limit of experimentally feasible range of concentrations) is not classifiable (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1999)).

Name: Silicic acid, (H4SiO4), tetraethyl ester
Rationale for classification: There was description in DFGOT (vol.3, 1992) about the mortality rate in the mist atmospheric exposure test which used rats. But there was no data of LC50 value, and category could not be specificked. Therefore, it cannot be classified since data is insufficient.

Name: o-Phenylenediamine
Rationale for classification: Based on the rat LC50 (inhalation of dust) value of 0.15mg/L (4 hours) (ACGIH (7th, 2001)).

Name: 2,4-Dichlorophenoxyacetic acid
Rationale for classification: There is no this product data. But was set as Category 4 based on that rat LC50 value of sodium salt and dimethylamine salt are ,respectively, >0.64mg/L and >3.7mg/L (no death case in 2.7mg/L, 2 death cases in 3.7mg/L)(all being 4-hour exposure)(Agricultural Chemical Registration Data, 1992).

Name: Bromomethane; Methyl bromide
Rationale for classification: Due to the fact that the substance is "gas" according to the GHS definition and inhalation of its dust/mist is not expected.

Name: Butyl acetate
Rationale for classification: It was set as Category 4 based on the rat inhalation test toxicity value of 391ppm (1.85mg/L) (ACGIH (2001)).

Name: 2-Hydroperoxy-2-phenylpropane
Rationale for classification: Saturated vapor pressure level of this substance at 25degC is 4 ppm. Since LC50 value of the 4-hour inhalation exposure test employing rats is 220 ppm (Patty (5th, 2001), IUCLID (2000)), equivalent is 1.4 mg/L by applying the mist standard, and it was classified into Category 4.

Name: Phosphonothioic acid, phenyl-, O-(2,4-dichlorophenyl) O-ethyl ester
pyraclofos
Rationale for classification: It was set as category 4 based on rat LC50 = 1.46mg/L (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data) of 4-hour exposure.

Name: Cadmium chloride (CdCl2), hydrate (2:5)
Rationale for classification:
Data without.
(In the risk phrases of EU-Annex I (Access on Jun.2005) of a cadmium chloride (anhydride), it is supposed that inhalation toxicity is very high.)

Name: heptan-3-one
Rationale for classification: From description that death was not acknowledged at 2000ppm in the 4-hour (equivalent 9.323mg/L) inhalation exposure test using rats (ACGIH 7th (2001), PATTY 4th (1994)), it was set as the outside of Category.

Name: Sodium dichromate
Rationale for classification: It was set as category 2 based on rat LC50 = 0.2mg/L (EU-RAR (2005)).

Name: Ethanol
Rationale for classification: "Rat inhalation LC50 (4h) = about 63000ml/m3 = 63000ppm (based on the definition of DFG. DFGOT (1996))". Since it was over the ethanol saturated vapor pressure pressures concentrations of 56580ppm in 20degC, it was classified as an inhalation test by mist. Furthermore, based on 63000ppm*1.88mg/m3 = 118mg/L >12.5mg/L (mist 5mg/L(mist 4 Category) *2.5), it considered as the outside of Category.

Name: Sodium dimethyldithiocarbamate
Rationale for classification: Classification not possible due to lack of data

Name: 4-(1,3-benzothiazol-2-yldisulfanyl)morpholine
Rationale for classification: Classification not possible due to lack of data

Name: tert-Butyl 4-({[(1,3-dimethyl-5-phenoxy-4-pyrazolyl)methylidene]aminooxy}methyl)benzoate; Fenpyroximate
Rationale for classification: Based on the rat LC50 (inhalation route) value of 0.33mg/L (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (2002)).

Name: 2-methyl-m-phenylene diamine
Rationale for classification: Classification not possible due to lack of data

Name: Cyanamide
Rationale for classification: There is a rat dust inhalation test result (Agricultural-Chemicals abstracts (2002)), that contains 57% of calcium cyanamide. And it is not a test result of cyanamide active ingredient, it cannot be classified.

Name: Cyclohexane, 5-isocyanato-1-(isocyanatomethyl)-1,3,3-trimethyl-
Rationale for classification: Since the saturated vapor pressures concentrations pressure of this product is 0.396ppm, it is presumed that LC50 value acquired by all inhalation study was acquired in mist conditions. Based on LC50 = 0.786mg/L calculated by the technical guide using three test results of rats (CERI Hazard Data (2000), MOE Risk Assessment(2004), and ACGIH (2001)), it was set as Category 3.

Name: 2-Naphthol
Rationale for classification: It was set as Category 4 based on LC50 value of an inhalation administration test using female male rats, that is 2.2mg/L/4H (2200mg/m3/4H) (SIDS, 2006; IUCLID, 2000).

Name: N,N-Dimethyl-1,2,3-trithian-5-amine
Rationale for classification: It was set as Category 4 based on rat LC50 = 1.02mg/L which is the lower value of LC50 = 1.02mg/L (male) and LC50 = 1.20mg/L (female) (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data).

Name: 1-chloro-1-nitropropane
Rationale for classification: It was set as the outside of Category based on mouse LC50 = 49mg/L (DFGOT vol.1 (1991)) of inhalation study done with mist.

Name: 1-Naphthylamine
Rationale for classification: There is the data stating that rat LC50 (4 hours) value was >0.056mg/L (IUCLID (2000), HSDB (Access on Oct 2005)). But it was not able to judge whether it would correspond to Category of except for category 1 from this data.

Name: Perfluoro(octane-1-sulfonic acid)
Rationale for classification: Classification is not possible because there is no data. In addition, it is written that LC50 value is 5.2 mg/L (4-hour equivalent: 1.3 mg/L) about Potassium perfluorooctane-1-sulfonate (CAS No.2795-39-3) of a related substance (the 6th volume of the MOE Risk Assessment (2008)).

Name: Divanadium pentaoxide
Rationale for classification: Based on the testing data of rat LC50 (4 hour inhalation exposure) of 4.29mg/L (IUCLID, 2000).

Name: Sodium chlorite
Rationale for classification: Since there are two rat LC50 values: 0.23mg/L (the original is 230mg/m3) (RTECS (2003)) and purity equivalent 0.235mg/L (=0.29*0.809) (IUCLID (2000)), 0.23mg/L of higher toxicity was adopted and set to category 2.

Name: 4-chlorobenzyl N-(2,4-dichlorophenyl)-2-(1H-1,2,4-triazol-1-yl)thioacetimidate
Rationale for classification: Classification cannot be determined, though the available rat inhalation study reported the LC50 value of >1.02mg/L (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1993)).

Name: 1,2,4-Trimethylbenzene
Rationale for classification: Saturated vapor pressure level of this substance at 25degC is 14.60 mg/L (2,969 ppm). Since LC50 value of the 4-hour inhalation exposure test employing rats is 18 mg/L (the 6th volume (2008) of the MOE Risk Assessment, RTECS (2008)), it was classified into "Not classified" by applying the mist standard. EU classification is Xn; R20 (EU-Annex I).

Name: 2,4-bis(ethylamino)-6-methylthio-1,3,5-triazine
Rationale for classification: Classification cannot be determined, though the available rat inhalation study reported the LC50 value of >4.88mg/L (4 hours) (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1988)).

Name: temephos
Rationale for classification: There is only data LC50 >1.3mg/L in the study considered to be based on a dust. So it cannot be classified.

Name: Benzene, 1-chloro-2-nitro-
Rationale for classification: It was set as Category 4 based on rat LC50 (4hr) = 495ppm (equivalent 3.18mg/L) (SIDS (2001)). In addition, the saturated concentration of this product is 24ppm, and it is presumed that the inhalation study was done in dust and mists conditions.

Name: p-Phenylenediamine
Rationale for classification: Based on the rat LC50 (inhalation of dust) value of 920mg/L (4 hours) (CERI Hazard Data 2001-31 (2002)).

Name: Alkanes, C10-13, chloro(shortchain chlorinated paraffins)
Rationale for classification: It is written that there is no mortality with 3.3 mg/L of 1-hour exposure amount in carbon number C12/ chloridization rate 59%, and there is no mortality with 48 mg/L of 1-hour exposure amount in carbon number C10-C13/ chloridization rate 50% in the inhalation exposure test (EU-RAR (1999)). Since saturated vapor pressure at 25degC is 0.000037-0.00014 mg/L (carbon number C10-C13/ chloridization rate 50%), the mist standard is applied. Since it was presumed that 4-hour equivalent LC50 values are >0.83 mg/L and >12 mg/L ,respectively, it was classified into "Not classified".

Name: Dodecan-1-ol
Rationale for classification: It is written that in 1-hour, 6-hour, or 18-hour inhalation exposure test employing rats, there was no mortality with 1.05 mg/L in any exposure time (SIDS (1992)). Since it is a liquid whose saturated vapor pressure level at 25degC is 0.0086 mg/L, 4-hour LC50 value equivalent is considered to be >0.2625 mg/L when applying the mist standard. Since classification cannot be specified, classification is not possible.

Name: Acenaphthene
Rationale for classification: Classification not possible due to lack of data

Name: fentin acetate
Rationale for classification: From rat inhalation LC50 value (male: 0.044mg/L/4H, female: 0.069mg/L/4H)(JMPR 827, 1991), the lower male data (male: 0.044mg/L/4H) was adopted, and it was set as Category 1.

Name: Distannoxane, hexabutyl-
Rationale for classification: Based on rat inhalation LC50 value 65mg/m3/4H (= 0.065mg/L/4H) (DFGOT 1 (1991); CICAD 14 (1999); ATSDR (2005)), it was set as Category 2.

Name: S-4-chlorobenzyl N,N-diethylthiocarbamate
Rationale for classification: The available rat inhalation studies reported the LC50 value of >2.43mg/L, but there are no test data available for higher doses (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (2004)).

Name: Distillates (petroleum), solvent-refined heavy paraffinic; Distillates (petroleum), solvent-refined light naphthenic; Lubricating oils (petroleum), C15-30, hydrotreated neutral oil-based; Lubricating oils (petroleum), C20-50, hydrotreated neutral oil-based; Petroleum; Paraffin oils
Rationale for classification: Category 4 because of "SPECIES: Rat;  ENDPOINT: LC50 = 2.18 mg/L." (IUCLID, 2000)

Name: o-Chloroaniline
Rationale for classification: Based on the LC50 value (4 hours) of 2.02mg/L (equivalent to 388ppm), calculated from the testing data of rat LC50 (1 hour) of 775ppm (CERI Hazard Data 99-25 (2000)), and the LC50 (4 hours) of 4.16mg/L (MOE Risk Assessment vol.3 (2004)) exceeded the saturated vapour concentration (350ppm) under a saturated vapour pressure of 35Pa (25degC), the substance was considered as "mist exposure" and was classified based on the LC50 (4 hours) value of 2.02mg/L representing the lower of the two data.

Name: cadusafos
Rationale for classification: It was set as Category 1 based on rat LC50 (4 hours) = 0.026mg/L of the inhalation toxicity study (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data).

Name: aldrin
Rationale for classification: From description that nine among ten rats died from 1-hour exposure of 0.108mg/L (4-hour equivalent 0.027mg/L) in the vapors and particles inhalation exposure tests (ATSDR (2002)), it was set as Category 1.

Name: 1-methylnaphthalene
Rationale for classification: Classification not possible due to lack of data

Name: Pentanal
Rationale for classification: There was description that three among three rat died from 48000ppm 1.2-hour exposure (4 hour equivalent: 50.6mg/L) (PATTY (4th, 1994)). But it was presupposed that it cannot classify since data is insufficient for specifying Category.

Name: Amitrol
Rationale for classification: Classification not possible due to lack of data

Name: 2-[(Thiocyanatomethyl)sulfanyl]-1,3-benzothiazole
Rationale for classification: Saturated vapor pressure level at 25degCis 0.00041 ppm (4*10^-6 mg/L). Since LC50 value with 0.1 mg/L of 4-hour inhalation exposure test employing rats (CERI/NITE Hazard Assessment Report (2008)) was larger than saturated vapor pressure level, it was classified into Category 2 by applying the dust and mist standard.

Name: 2-tert-Butyl-5-methylphenol
Rationale for classification: Classification not possible due to lack of data

Name: n-Butyl methacrylate
Rationale for classification: Because the rat LC50 (inhalation) value of 28.5mg/L (equivalent to 4,810ppm) (CERI Hazard Data 2001-49 (2002)) exceeded the saturated vapour concentration (2,790ppm) under a saturated vapour pressure of 282Pa (25degC), the substance was considered as "mist exposure," and the obtained LC50 exceeded the upper limit value of Category 4 (5mg/L) by more than 2.5 fold.

Name: Stannane, tributyl-, mono(naphthenoyloxy) derivs
Rationale for classification: Because the rat LC50 (4 hour inhalation of vapour) value of 0.152mg/L (DFGOT Vol.1 (1990)) exceeded 90% of the saturated vapour concentration (9*10^(-4)ppm (equivalent to 1*10^(-5)mg/L)) under a saturated vapour pressure of 9*10^(-5)Pa (20degC) (EHC 116 (1990)), the substance was considered as "mist exposure" and was classified into Category 2.

Name: pyrazophos
Rationale for classification: Classification not possible due to lack of data

Name: N,N-diethyl-3-(2,4,6-trimethylphenylsulfonyl)-1H-1,2,4-triazole-1-carboxamide
Rationale for classification: Classification cannot be determined, though the available rat inhalation study reported the LC50 value of >1.97mg/L (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1995)).

Name: Furan
Rationale for classification: Classification not possible due to lack of data

Name: 3,4-Dichloroaniline
Rationale for classification: Since it is written in EU-RAR (2006) that LC50 values of 4-hour aerosol inhalation exposure test employing rats are >0.631 mg/L (OECD TG403), and 3.3 mg/L, it was classified into Category 4 based on the definite value 3.3 mg/L.. In addition, in EU classification, T; 23/24/25 (EU-Annex I).

Name: 3,5-dichloroaniline
Rationale for classification: Classification is not possible because there is no data. In addition, EU classification of 3,4-Dichloroaniline (CAS No.95-76-1) which is a constitutional isomer is T;23/24/25 (EU-Annex I).

Name: Xylidine
Rationale for classification: There is no report of an isomer mixture. There is data of rat LC50: 1.53mg/L (DFGOTvol.19 (2003)) about 2, 4-Xylidine. The concentration of the saturated vapor at 25degC is 180 ppm (0.89mg/L), and 1.53mg/L is considered to be mist. And if it is exposure for 4 hours, it is equivalent to category 2. However, there is no publication of exposure time, it cannot be classified by this data.

Name: (3,5,6-trichloro-2-pyridyl)oxyacetic acid
Rationale for classification: Based on the rat LC50 (inhalation route) value of >5.43mg/L (4 hours) (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1996)).

Name: disulfoton
Rationale for classification: It was set as Category 1 based on female rat LC50 = about 0.015mg/L (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1987)).

Name: Diethylphthalate
Rationale for classification: From description that death was not acknowledged in the test using the rat (PATTY 4th (1994)) by 511ppm of 6-hour exposure (4-hour equivalent 6.95mg/L), it was set as the outside of Category.

Name: Ethyl 2-[4-(6-chloro-2-quinoxalinyloxy)phenoxy]propionate; Quizalofop-ethyl
Rationale for classification: Based on the rat LC50 (inhalation route) value of 5.8mg/L (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1983)).

Name: Parathion, methyl-
Rationale for classification: The sexual differences which exceeds the difference during an examination on 11 rat LC50 value (EHC 145 (1993), ATSDR (2001), JMPR 902 (1995)) is not acknowledged. It was set as Category 2 based on 0.0611mg/L calculated by statistical work including males and females.

Name: Benzene, (dichloromethyl)-
Rationale for classification: It was set as Category 4 based on 4-hour converted values 4.3mg/L of rat LC50 = 654ppm (CERI Hazard Data (2000)).

Name: m-Xylene
Rationale for classification: Because the LC50 value (4 hours) of 8,977ppm, calculated from the testing data of rat LC50 (6-hour inhalation) of 5,984ppm/kg (EHC 190 (1997)), exceeded the saturated vapour concentration (6,600ppm) under a saturated vapour pressure of 0.67kPa (20degC), the substance was considered as "mist exposure" and was classified based on the LC50 (4 hours) value of 39.59mg/kg.

Name: O-4-cyanophenyl O,O-dimethyl phosphorothioate
Rationale for classification: Classification cannot be determined, though the available rat inhalation study reported the LC50 value of >1.5mg/L (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1988)).

Name: 1-Chloro-1,1-difluoroethane; HCFC-142b
Rationale for classification: Due to the fact that the substance is "gas" according to the GHS definition and inhalation of its dust/mist is not expected.

Name: Benxyl acetate
Rationale for classification: Classification not possible due to lack of data

Name: 2,4-Imidazolidinedione, 1,3-dichloro-5,5-dimethyl-
Rationale for classification: Since death was seen at rat 1 hour exposure tests: 20g/m3 (4 hour equivalent: 5mg/L (upper limit of Category 4)) (RTECS (2004)), it was set as Category 5.

Name: Tetraalkyllead
Rationale for classification: Unidentified substance (Refer to the data of an individual substance.)

Name: Ammonium perchlorate
Rationale for classification: There is only a data with rat lethal concentration: >0.3mg/L (RTECS, 2005), and it cannot be classified since data is insufficient.

Name: 2-Phenyl-2-[(2-phenylpropan-2-yl)peroxy]propane
Rationale for classification: Since it is a solid, a dust standard is applied. Since 6-hour LCLo value of rats is >0.09 mg/L (4-hour equivalent >0.14 mg/L) (DFGOT vol.3 (1992), Patty (5th, 2001)), the classification cannot be specified, and classification is not possible.

Name: Celluloid, in blocks, rods, rolls, sheets, tubes, etc.
Ethylene oxide
Rationale for classification: Due to the fact that the substance is "gas" according to the GHS definition and inhalation of its dust/mist is not expected.

Name: Mevinphos
Rationale for classification: Calculated on based on rat LC50 (1 hour) value: 14.4ppm (4-hour equivalent 0.0329mg/L) and 0.0098mg/L (4-hour equivalent 0.0025mg/L) (ACGIH, 2003), approximately 14ppm (4-hour equivalent 0.032mg/L) (PATTY 4th, 1994). Since the calculated values were 0.00609mg/L, they were set to category 1.

Name: Methyl 4-hydroxybenzoate
Rationale for classification: Classification not possible due to lack of data

Name: 2-tert-Butyl-5-(4-tert-butylbenzylthio)-4-chloro-3(2H)-pyridazinone; Pyridaben
Rationale for classification: Based on the rat LC50 (inhalation route) value of 0.62mg/L (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1987)).

Name: N-methyldithiocarbamic acid
Rationale for classification: Based on the rat LC50 (inhalation route) value of 1.98mg/L (4 hours) (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1984)).

Name: N-tert-butyl-N'-(4-ethylbenzoyl)-3,5-dimethylbenzohydrazide
Rationale for classification: Classification cannot be determined, though the available rat inhalation study reported the LC50 value of >0.43mg/L (4 hours) (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1993)).

Name: Tungsten hexafluoride
Rationale for classification: Due to the fact that the substance is "gas" according to the GHS definition and inhalation of its dust/mist is not expected.

Name: endothal
Rationale for classification: Since it was rat inhalation LC50 (mist, 4 hours) = 1.85mg/L (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1994)), it was set as Category 4.

Name: 2-butylphenyl methylcarbamate
Rationale for classification: Rat LC50 (4 hours) value: >2.50mg/L, and one female died from 1.92mg/L and three females died from 2.50mg/L (Agricultural-Chemicals abstracts). But the category could not be specified only by these data and it cannot be classified since data is insufficient.

Name: Beryllium sulfate, Tetrahydrate
Rationale for classification: Based on the LC50 value of 0.029 mg BeSO4.4H2O/L calculated from the testing data of rat LC50 (4 hour inhalation) of 0.15 mg beryllium/m3 (DFGOT Vol.21 (2005)).

Name: Polymer of 4,4'-isopropylidenediphenol and 1-chloro-2,3-epoxypropane (liquid); Bisphenol A type epoxy resin (liquid)
Chloroethane
Rationale for classification: Due to the fact that the substance is "gas" according to the GHS definition and inhalation of its dust/mist is not expected.

Name: S-Ethyl hexahydro-1H-azepine-1-carbothioate; Molinate
Rationale for classification: Based on the rat LC50 (inhalation route) value of 1.39mg/L (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1989)).

Name: Butylated hydroxyanisole(BHA)
Rationale for classification: Classification not possible due to lack of data

Name: O-Ethyl O-4-nitrophenyl phenylphosphonothioate; EPN
Rationale for classification: Based on the rat LC50 (4 hours) value of 0.0265mg/L, calculated from the testing data of rat LC50 (inhalation) of 0.106mg/L (1 hour) (MOE Risk Assessment vol. 4 (2005)).

Name: Esfenvalerate
Rationale for classification: It was set as Category 2 based on inhalation by mists in a rat LC50 (4hr) = 0.48mg/L (JMPR (2002)).

Name: 2-Chlorophenol
Rationale for classification: Classification not possible due to lack of data

Name: 2-Ethylhexan-1-yl diphenyl phosphate
Rationale for classification: Saturated vapor pressure level of this substance (150degC)is 3.94 mg/L. Since the measured concentration in initiation temperature 125degC is 4.8 mg/L, and LC0 value is >4.8 mg/L in the 4-hour inhalation exposure test employing rats (IUCLID (2000)), classification cannot be specified when applying the mist standard, and classification is not possible.

Name: 4,6-Dinitro-o-cresol
Rationale for classification: Based on the rat LC50 (4-hour inhalation of dust/mist) value of 0.23mg/L (EHC 220 (2000).

Name: cyhexatin
Rationale for classification: Classification not possible due to lack of data

Name: 2-(4-chloro-6-ethylamino-1,3,5-triazin-2-yl)amino-2-methylpropiononitrile
Rationale for classification: Classification cannot be determined, though the available rat inhalation study reported the LC50 value of >0.809mg/L (4 hours) (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1983)).

Name: O-Ethyl O-(6-nitro-m-tolyl) sec-butylphosphoramidothioate; Butamifos
Rationale for classification: Classification not possible, though no evidence of death was found at the highest dose of 1.2mg/L in rat acute toxicity studies using the inhalation route of exposure (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1983)).

Name: copper bis(dimethyldithiocarbamate)
Rationale for classification: It was either of Category 2 - Category 4 from the description that the rat LCLo (4 hours) value was 0.21mg/L (RTECS (2005)). But it was not able to be specified since data is insufficient. Therefore, it cannot be classified.

Name: Sodium alpha-dodecan-1-yl-omega-(sulfonatooxy)poly(oxyethylene)
Rationale for classification: Classification not possible due to lack of data

Name: 2,4'-dichloro-alpha-(5-pyrimidinyl)benzhydryl alcohol
Rationale for classification: Classification cannot be determined, though the available rat inhalation study reported the LC50 value of >2.04mg/L (4 hours) (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1980)).

Name: Cyanamide, calcium salt (1:1)
Rationale for classification: About inhalation, there is description of "LC50 are maximum allowable concentrations, and 13g or more of 50% aqueous solutions of calcium cyanamide per m3" (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (2000)). And LC50 became >6.5mg/L (mist), it was set as Category 5.

Name: Hydrazine sulfate
Rationale for classification: Classification not possible due to lack of data

Name: Malathon
Rationale for classification: Since the category can not be specified only by the data (Agricultural-Chemicals abstracts) that rat LC50 (4 hours) value is >3.450mg/L, it cannot be classified.

Name: 5-Allyl-1,3-benzodioxole
Rationale for classification: Classification not possible due to lack of data

Name: p-Bromo-2-fluoroacetanilide
Rationale for classification: There is data on the mouse. But exposure time is unknown, and since data is insufficient, it cannot classify.

Name: 3,5-diiodo-4-octanoyloxybenzonitrile
Rationale for classification: Classification cannot be determined, though the available rat dermal study reported the LC50 value of >2.4mg/L (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1990)).

Name: 2-Thioxo-3,5-dimethyltetrahydro-2H-1,3,5-thiadiazine; Dazomet
Rationale for classification: Based on the rat LC50 (inhalation route) value of 7.29mg/L (Agricultural Chemical Registration Data (1990)).

Name: O-Ethyl S,S-diphenyl phosphorodithioate; Edifenphos; EDDP
Rationale for classification: Based on the rat LC50 (4 hour inhalation of vapour) value of 0.65mg/L (HSDB (2006)) exceeded 90% of the saturated vapour concentration (3.6*10^(-4)ppm) under a saturated vapour pressure of 2.70*10^(-7)mmHg (25degC) [equivalent to 36.0microPa (25degC)] (HSDB (2006)), the substance was considered as "mist exposure" and was classified as Category 3.

Name: Paraformaldehyde
Rationale for classification: Category 4 because of "SPECIES: Rat (aspiration); ENDPOINT: LC50; VALUE:1.07mg/L" (RTECS, 2005)

Name: Palygorskite
Rationale for classification: Classification is not possible because there is no data. In addition, it is written that there is only a little evaporation at 20degC, but it reaches the harmful level of suspended particulate quickly when it spreads (ICSC (2005)).

Name: iodine
Rationale for classification: There is a data with rat LCLo (1 hour) value: 0.8mg/L (4-hour equivalent 0.2 mg/L) (PATTY (4th, 1994)). But there is no data about LC50 value, and Category could not be specified. Therefore, it cannot be classifed since data is insufficient.

Name: Disodium disulphite
Rationale for classification: Classification not possible due to lack of data
